<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Prices Jump Sinks Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors were rudely reminded this past week  
that inflation is very much alive, with a trio of reports showing 
the economy is still growing -- and prices are rising -- at a strong 
clip. 
</P>
<P>
	Separate reports Friday showed a bigger-than-expected rise in  
consumer prices, strong gains in industrial output and consumers' 
continued willingness to spend. 
</P>
<P>
	They were a wake-up call to investors who have been bidding  
stock prices ever higher on the assumption that, despite the 
economy's fabulous growth, inflation was in long hibernation -- if 
not dead. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will reignite this debate about whether you can run an  
economy with 4.3 percent unemployment and no inflation,'' said 
David Blitzer, chief economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors worried that Friday's data would push the Federal  
Reserve to raise interest rates at its Open Market Committee 
meeting Tuesday. Although most economists still don't believe 
central bankers will tighten credit that soon, they said the 
reports could set the stage for a tightening later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``They can't turn a blind eye toward this,'' said Bryan  
Piskorowski, market analyst at Prudential Securities. ``It's not 
the kind of information that one can explain away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrials skidded 205 points on the reports and  
closed down 193.87 Friday at 10,913.32, one day after rising to a 
new closing high of 11,107.19. The Dow fell 118.27 for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices crashed too, pushing the yield on the 30-year  
Treasury bond up to 5.92 percent and perilously close to an 
important 6 percent level. Higher rates often send stock prices 
lower because they raise corporate borrowing costs and jeopardize 
profits, while at the same time slowing consumer spending. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts noted that stocks often fall ahead of Fed policy  
meetings. This is especially true now, they said, because stocks 
have been trading at very high prices on the assumption that 
interest rates would remain stable. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Vitner, an economist at First Union Corp. in Charlotte,  
N.C., said the current inflation picture is ``not as bad as the 
headline numbers suggest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department reported an unexpectedly sharp 0.7 percent  
rise in consumer prices in April. Minus huge increases in energy 
costs, core prices rose a surprising 0.4 percent, the most since 
January of 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	But that was only payback for years of uncommonly tame  
inflation, Vitner said. Inflation as measured by consumer prices is 
rising at a manageable 2.3 percent annual pace, ``right where the 
Fed expected it to be,'' Vitner said. And the Labor Department 
reported Thursday that wholesale prices, minus food and energy, 
climbed a tiny 0.1 percent in April. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report Friday, the Fed reported factory output  
rose 0.6 percent in April, its strongest gain since the summer of 
1998. Factories operated in April at 80.6 percent of capacity. That 
was up from a revised 80.4 percent in March, but still very low, 
Vitner said. 
</P>
<P>
	And the gains in the manufacturing sector, while they were  
strong in April, were not across the board. Steel production, for 
example, dropped nearly 2 percent, Vitner noted. ``I can't see a 
true turn in the manufacturing sector without seeing some sort of 
revival in steel production.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's third report, the University of Michigan said its  
consumer sentiment index, which attempts to measure consumers' 
propensity to spend, had risen so far this month to 106.4 from 
104.6 in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Although that could stir inflation fears as well, it could also  
support stock prices, which have been rising since 1992 in large 
part because consumers keep spending and boosting corporate 
profits. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a tug-of-war going on between good news on  
profitability and bad news on interest rates,'' conceded John 
Lonski, senior economist at Moody's Investors Service. 
</P>
<P>
	The real test for the stock market, he said, is whether  
corporations can continue to convert the buoyant economic trends 
into bottom-line profits. And with earnings up between 15 and 20 
percent annually from 1994 through 1997, that's a tough act to 
follow, Lonski said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's trading, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 composite fell  
29.76 to 1,337.80, down 7.20 for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq composite declined 54.14 to 2,527.86 Friday, adding  
24.24 for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 12.90 to 638.45 Friday, losing  
2.79 for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Stock Exchange index fell 11.58 to 788.81 Friday,  
up 1.52 for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 7.71 to 443.13  
Friday but rose 7.02 for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wilshire 5000 index, which represents the combined market  
value of all NYSE, American and Nasdaq issues, closed at $12.3 
trillion, up $100 billion from the previous week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
