<HEADLINE> Jazz Fans Go Crazy at Game 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Karl Malone asked Utah Jazz fans to ``get  
a little crazy'' for Sunday's Game 5 against the Sacramento Kings. 
</P>
<P>
	That's like asking a shark to get a little hungry.  
</P>
<P>
	There was pandemonium in and around the Delta Center all day as  
Utah's notoriously vocal, rambunctious fans were in peak form. 
Hundreds gathered on the arena grounds hours before the game, 
competing for tickets from local radio stations and generally 
making noise. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Kings arrived at the arena, they were greeted by  
chanting fans carrying everything from cowbells to miniature police 
sirens. The Jazz complained about Arco Arena fans ringing cowbells 
and blowing whistles from the stands behind their bench in Friday's 
Game 4 win in Sacramento. 
</P>
<P>
	``We took it personally when the people in Sacramento were  
razzing our guys,'' said Provo contractor Danny Guise, 31, who had 
his face painted and carried a sign reading ``The Kings Must Die!'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Karl and some of the guys say we really help when we're loud  
and in the other team's face, so we're just doing our job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Inside the arena, dozens of fans were decked out in camouflage  
and bright orange clothing, and dozens of wildlife calls could be 
heard as the two teams warmed up. Malone, an avid hunter, asked the 
fans to do just that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm looking forward to running through that tunnel tomorrow  
and playing this game. My friends are going to have elk calls and 
duck calls and all that,'' Malone said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of signs dotted the stands, with sentiments ranging  
from ``Sacto is for whom the cowbell tolls,'' to ``You messed with 
the wrong fans. We'll make Arco Arena sound like church.'' The 
Jazz's mascot, Bear, rang a bell the size of a Thanksgiving turkey 
right behind the Kings' bench. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jazz unleashed pregame fireworks that incited the crowd to  
deafening noise levels. The loudest cheers came for John Stockton, 
who hit the 23-foot jumper with seven-tenths of a second to play 
that won Game 4 for the Jazz. 
</P>
<P>
	The noise added another level of excitement to an already tense  
game. Malone, Corliss Williamson and Chris Webber picked up 
technical fouls in the first 1:45, and Vlade Divac got tangled up 
with Greg Ostertag in a shoving match. 
</P>
<P>
	The noise reached deafening levels when the Kings called a  
timeout after falling behind 14-3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
