<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pollsters Face Threat From Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETE BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Pollsters who just experienced one  
of their most influential years now face a triple threat: increased 
scrutiny by critics, declining public response to poll interviewers 
and the lure of Internet surveys. 
</P>
<P>
	These were major concerns of pollsters who gathered over the  
weekend for the annual meeting of the American Association for 
Public Opinion Research. 
</P>
<P>
	The role played by public opinion in President Clinton's sex  
scandal and impeachment trial was a frequent theme at the weekend 
sessions. While public support for the president did not prevent an 
impeachment trial, many analysts believe it contributed to his 
political survival. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last year solidified the importance of public opinion,''  
said New York City pollster Warren Mitofsky. ``The public made it 
abundantly clear over and over again -- they were supporting Bill 
Clinton as president, but condemning his behavior.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton's impeachment trial raised the political stakes for  
polling, and the poll results that backed him became part of the 
debate. 
</P>
<P>
	Public opinion polls became ``political footballs to be kicked  
around,'' said Kathleen Frankovic, director of polling for CBS 
News. 
</P>
<P>
	The unwillingness of some people to participate in polls, a  
problem pollsters call ``non-response,'' also was discussed by 
pollsters at the conference. 
</P>
<P>
	A study by the Pew Research Center for the People &AMP; the Press  
showed no difference in low and high response polls, but pollsters 
say they do not fully understand the effects of low response. 
</P>
<P>
	The non-response problem has grown as people have more high-tech  
phone screening devices, less use for inquiries from strangers and 
the perception that they have less time, say pollsters. 
</P>
<P>
	Some estimate that response levels have dropped about 10  
percentage points over the last decade from levels that had ranged 
between 50 percent to 60 percent, depending on the definition used. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're beginning to address this problem head-on, to find out  
what difference response rates make in terms of quality,'' said 
Michael Traugott, incoming president of AAPOR. 
</P>
<P>
	A more controversial issue at this meeting was Internet polls,  
which have sprung up on many Web sites and threaten to drown out 
scientific polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Traditional pollsters said over the weekend they are considering  
a rating system to distinguish between scientifically designed 
polls, which pick a random geographic and weighted sample of the 
entire population, and those which do not. 
</P>
<P>
	The polling firm Harris Black International made a pitch to the  
group that the Internet can be used effectively for election 
polling by drawing a large pool of Web users and then finding a 
representative poll sample from that group. 
</P>
<P>
	But most in the polling field argue the company cannot draw a  
representative sample of the nation's population off the Internet, 
which is used by about 40 percent of Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	Murray Edelman, editorial director of Voter News Service and  
incoming AAPOR vice president, said Internet polling will never 
supplant the highest quality probability polls. But he acknowledged 
the Internet efforts are likely to ``reshape polling'' at some 
levels because of their convenience and relative low cost. 
</P>
<P>
	VNS is a partnership of the ABC, CBS, CNN, NBC and Fox  
television networks and The Associated Press that conducts state 
and national exit polls on Election Day. 
</P>
<P>
	George Terhanian, director of Internet Research at Harris Black  
acknowledges limitations of the current population using the 
Internet, but says: ``We will gladly take a few hits in order to 
get this right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite their concerns, pollsters said the last year offered a  
unique environment to practice their craft and reinforce the 
accuracy of polling. 
</P>
<P>
	Traugott, AAPOR president, said the intense focus of pollsters  
on the Clinton scandal provided quick public judgments that proved 
stable for the duration. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure we'll see soon another instance,'' Traugott said,  
``in which there was such highly focused polling activity on such a 
limited set of topics.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
