<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rapids 1, Fire 0 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Joey DiGiamarino scored in the 12th minute Sunday  
on a blast from about 20 yards out as the Colorado Rapids beat the 
Chicago Fire 1-0. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the fifth straight win for the Rapids (5-2), a team  
record, and their first shutout of the year. The Fire (5-3) lost 
for the first time in regulation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would have liked to have seen more possessions down the  
stretch, but sometimes you just have to dig in and fight,'' 
Colorado coach Glenn Myernick said. 
</P>
<P>
	DiGiamarino took a pass from Wolde Harris and dribbled between  
two Fire defenders before freeing the ball by kicking it forward 
and to his left. He outran the defenders, caught up to the ball and 
then slammed it into the goal on a diagonal kick past a diving Zach 
Thornton. 
</P>
<P>
	It was DiGiamarino's first goal in regulation this season. He's  
converted two of his four attempts in shootouts. Ross Paule also 
was credited with an assist on the goal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fire had what looked like a can't-miss opportunity in the  
47th minute, when Roman Kosecki was fouled in the penalty box by 
Anders Limpar. Lubos Kubik, who hadn't missed a penalty kick in six 
tries, took the shot, but it banged off the left side of the 
crossbar. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the Fire's first missed penalty kick in eight tries.  
</P>
<P>
	Colorado goalkeeper Marcus Hahnemann had nine saves, including a  
key stop in the 78th minute. Chris Armas took a straight-on shot 
only to have Hahnemann block it. Armas looked like he might get a 
second shot at the ball, but Hahnemann made another save. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 87th minute, Hahnemann deflected a shot from Wolff and  
the ball bounced over the goal. 
</P>
<P>
	The game was part of a doubleheader with the U.S. women's soccer  
team, which beat the Netherlands 3-0 in a tuneup for next month's 
Women's World Cup. Mia Hamm tied the record for international goals 
with her 107th, and also had an assist on Brandi Chastain's second 
goal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
