<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Midler Helps Save New York Garden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- On one side was the city, eager to sell 112  
vacant lots and cash in during a real estate boom. On other side 
were urban green thumbs who had turned the neglected plots from 
trash-strewn symbols of inner-city decay into lush flower beds and 
vegetable gardens. 
</P>
<P>
	In the middle was Bette Midler.  
</P>
<P>
	Activists dressed as ladybugs and sunflowers protested outside  
City Hall, without success. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani told them, 
``This isn't communism,'' suggesting they buy the land themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	The gardens brightened often bleak streets across the city, from  
the Lower East Side to the Bronx. But the city had always reserved 
the right to claim the lots for development. So, when the city's 
economic boom made the open space valuable, it put the plots on the 
auction block. 
</P>
<P>
	The gardeners -- some of whom had tended the plots for more than  
20 years -- objected loudly. 
</P>
<P>
	But it seemed no one in government was listening. Unable to get  
a meeting with the mayor, 30 staged a sit-in at City Hall in 
February. Festooned with fake flowers and plants, they printed 
songbooks and sang versions of civil rights-era songs with updated 
lyrics: ``We Shall Overcome'' became ``We Shall Till the Soil.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, a gardener dressed as a giant sunflower climbed a  
tree outside City Hall and refused to come down until the mayor 
came out. Instead, a police officer climbed the tree and arrested 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, unknown to the protesters, a coalition of  
environmental groups led by the nonprofit Trust for Public Land, 
was trying to save the gardens. 
</P>
<P>
	They resisted the idea of buying the land since the trust favors  
creating public land ownership, but there was no strong 
alternative, said Roberta Greene, spokeswoman for the New York 
Restoration Project, a group founded four years ago by Midler. 
</P>
<P>
	``When all the other efforts didn't seem to be going anywhere,''  
according to Greene, ``Midler said, 'Well, if worst comes to worst, 
we'll just buy them.''' 
</P>
<P>
	As negotiations proceeded without reaching a deal, the  
singer-actress stepped in Wednesday -- the morning before the 
auction -- and offered $250,000 of her own money and $1 million from 
her group to buy 51 gardens. 
</P>
<P>
	The Trust would pay $3 million -- including an additional $1  
million from Midler's group -- for the 61 others. 
</P>
<P>
	The $4.2 million total exceeded the $3.5 million the city hoped  
to get at auction. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're thrilled. This is a joyous occasion and means that these  
gardens will stay in perpetuity,'' Midler said in a statement. 
``I'm grateful to everyone who has helped us save these important 
neighborhood gardens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some protesting gardeners objected to being left out of the  
negotiating process. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are dismayed that the gardeners have been excluded,'' said  
Emerson Running Sky, one of 90 gardeners arrested in protests. 
``Such wrangling, even for noble reasons, does injury to our 
democracy and does little to empower the affected communities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The secrecy was essential, though, to reach a deal with city  
negotiators, said Susan Clark of the Trust for Public Land. 
</P>
<P>
	``People might be upset right now,'' Clark said. ``But their  
long-term reaction will be happiness, because the gardens got 
saved.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
