<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 11:21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Investment Firms Can't Woo Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- As American securities firms looked for new  
opportunities overseas, moving into Japan seemed like a no-brainer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese have one of the highest savings rates in the  
industrialized world, an aging population worried about building a 
nest egg and notoriously low interest rates on bank savings 
accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, nearly a year after beginning an aggressive  
expansion campaign here, Merrill Lynch, Fidelity Investments and 
other titans of Wall Street have yet to prove their worth to 
ordinary Japanese. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem: this country's compulsively conservative individual  
investor. 
</P>
<P>
	Statistics compiled by Japan's Investment Trusts Association  
show foreign firms are making inroads, but remain minor players in 
the country's mutual fund market. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch's new brokerage business, for example, expects to  
post a net loss of nearly $75 million in the last business year, 
which ended March 31. 
</P>
<P>
	And the amount of Japanese mutual fund money being managed by  
Morgan Stanley has actually dropped slightly in the past six 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's definitely going to take some time,'' said Donna Morris,  
senior vice president of the year-old Fidelity Brokerage Services 
Japan. ``The concept of `buy-and-hold' investing in Japan is very 
new.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Simply investing in stocks, in fact, is still seen by many here  
as akin to spending a day at the race track. 
</P>
<P>
	But many see that as likely to change.  
</P>
<P>
	Japan, experts note, is increasingly feeling pressures from a  
pension crisis, the rapidly aging society and diminished job 
security as the economy retrenches under the weight of a severe 
recession. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to capitalize on the situation, several leading Wall  
Street companies set up shop or signed alliances with domestic 
banks and brokers to win over Japan's small-potato investor -- whose 
13 percent average household savings rate is second only to France 
in the industrialized world. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch opened its Japanese retail brokerage last year and  
is running full-page newspaper advertisements with the 
English-language headline ``Bullish on Japan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's easy to see the potential here.  
</P>
<P>
	Industry experts say less than 3 percent of Japan's estimated $9  
trillion in personal assets are in mutual fund-type investments. 
More than 50 percent of the total is locked up in multi-year 
certificates of deposit (CDs) at banks with annual yields of around 
0.25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, that loyalty to savings accounts betrays a pervasive fear  
of the risk-taking involved with stock investments. 
</P>
<P>
	While Americans have grown accustomed to fat returns, the  
collapse of Japan's once high-flying stock market at the outset of 
this decade soured many here on shareholding. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark stock index stands today at less than half its  
peak value in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stocks are too much of a gamble for most people,'' said Koichi  
Yoneda, a 22-year-old who recently graduated from college. ``The 
Japanese way is low-risk, low-return.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, a rally on Tokyo's stock markets in the first few months  
of this year shows signs that at least some investors are taking a 
second look. 
</P>
<P>
	The value of share purchases by individuals in the first week of  
April exceeded purchases by corporate and foreign investors for the 
first time in almost three years. 
</P>
<P>
	And while the average Japanese may now still be skittish when it  
comes to personal finance, they may have to start making some hard 
choices soon. 
</P>
<P>
	The government is expected to unveil a new pension scheme by  
next year resembling the 401(k) plan in the United States, which 25 
million Americans have used to invest $1 trillion in tax-deferred 
income. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's plan will likely involve a shift from corporate-managed  
funds to investments selected by individual employees in personal 
accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	The increased freedom means greater risk because companies would  
no longer subsidize investments which perform poorly as they 
typically do now. 
</P>
<P>
	Pensions are also a problem.  
</P>
<P>
	PriceWaterhouseCoopers, the accounting firm, has estimated that  
underfunded pension obligations at companies in Japan may total 
more than $671 billion. Some small firms have simply pulled the 
plug on their pension plans because of massive funding shortfalls. 
</P>
<P>
	The full extent of the problem is unknown because companies here  
aren't required to disclose the information. But that will change 
next year, when new accounting rules go into effect. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's mandatory national pension plan, which is similar to the  
U.S. Social Security system, is also in trouble due to longer life 
spans and fewer births. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet for all the pessimism about Japan's financial future, some  
of the country's famously thrifty savers may find it hard to play 
the market with their hard-earned yen. 
</P>
<P>
	``People remain very afraid with regard to the preservation of  
their capital,'' said Ken Okamura, a strategist at Dresdner 
Kleinwort Benson (Asia) Ltd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
