<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Director: Clinton Image Hurt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANNES, France (AP) -- Chinese director Chen Kaige says President  
Clinton's image in China has been ruined by NATO's bombing of the 
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Chen, whose ``Farewell My Concubine'' shared top prize at the  
Cannes festival in 1993, is in town with his sweeping historical 
epic ``The Emperor and the Assassin.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he came to the festival ``with sadness and love'' after  
seeing his country's angry reaction to the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, he said, had won many admirers in China with his recent  
visit. ``People really fell in love with him,'' Chen said Sunday. 
``But now, his image is ruined.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three journalists were killed in the May 8 bombing.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	An unseasonal invasion of jellyfish is keeping the usual Cannes  
topless bathing beauties from cooling off in the Mediterranean this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marine Observatory in nearby Villefranche noted the unusual  
plague earlier this week, but offered no explanation. The pink, 
almost transparent creatures -- sometimes a foot or more long -- 
inflict a painful, electric sting, leaving welts and burn marks. 
Many hope better weather and stronger currents will wash them away. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	A Concorde supersonic jet was seen parked at the Nice airport  
Sunday, one of three on special shuttle duty ferrying well-heeled 
passengers to Paris and London from the Monaco Formula 1 Grand 
Prix. 
</P>
<P>
	The race, coinciding with the end of a four-day holiday weekend  
-- and of course the Cannes festival -- made Sunday one of the 
busiest days of the year: Almost 1,500 flights were expected in and 
out of Nice along with 100 helicopters from Monaco or Cannes. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Air France, the official carrier of the Cannes Film Festival, is  
pitching its 13 weekly nonstop flights from Paris to Los Angeles 
directly to Hollywood's movers and shakers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, she'll make you comfortable,'' says the caption under the  
picture of a beautiful, smiling stewardess. 
</P>
<P>
	``No, she won't try to sell you a screenplay.''  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The party season is in full force at Cannes. Some of the most  
high-profile bashes already have taken place. 
</P>
<P>
	At the annual MTV party, 1,000 guests -- mostly on the very young  
side -- danced to a DJ at Carlton Beach, providing a sleepless night 
for those staying across the street at the Carlton Hotel. Among 
those in attendance: rocker Jon Bon Jovi and actor Matthew 
McConaughey. 
</P>
<P>
	More star power was evident at the much more sedate daytime Cure  
by the Shore event, hosted by Lily Tartikoff, wife of the late 
entertainment executive Brandon Tartikoff. Peri Gilpin of TV's 
``Frasier'' was a co-host, and the fete attracted Darryl Hannah and 
Jeff Goldblum. 
</P>
<P>
	While a calypso band played, guests munched on sushi and  
barbecue, and little chocolate shells filled with rice pudding. 
</P>
<P>
	The hottest ticket, though, was probably the party Saturday  
night for the new ``Austin Powers'' movie. But guests at the Palm 
Beach nightclub were largely disappointed. The food was gone by 1 
a.m., and the stars -- including Mike Myers and Val Kilmer -- were 
cordoned off in a private area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
