<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gun Shows Prove Weapons Easy To Get </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENSBURG, Pa. (AP) -- Trench coats were banned at the  
Pennsylvania Gun Collector's Association gun show out of respect 
for the victims of the Colorado school shooting. The weapons the 
shooters used were easy to find, though. 
</P>
<P>
	At one table, William Phillips sold the kind of Hi Point 9 mm  
carbine rifle used by Dylan Klebold -- $149.99 in black or $154.99 
in chrome. For $69.99 he'll add a laser sight. The Mossburg 500 
Persuader pump-action shotgun model Eric Harris used lay on a dozen 
tables throughout space that formerly housed a department store -- 
$250 to $350. One buyer wrapped up a banned TEC DC-9 semiautomatic 
assault pistol, like the one Klebold toted -- $359. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Senate voted Friday to crack down on gun shows,  
firearms owners and dealers gathered at a gun show in America's 
heartland this weekend to barter, collect and commiserate about a 
country that has become increasingly hostile to their way of life. 
Dealers hawked everything from early American muskets to banned 
assault rifles and armor-piercing bullets. 
</P>
<P>
	But what many hoped to sell most was the message that adding to  
the nation's 30,000 gun laws won't prevent murder sprees like the 
one in Littleton, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you take all the firearms out of the hands of the honest  
citizens, there will be firearms out there in the community that 
someone has obtained illegally,'' said Richard Vensel, president of 
the Pennsylvania Gun Collectors Association, which hosted the show. 
``A criminal is not going to come to a show and try to purchase a 
firearm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Greensburg show, which saw an estimated 5,000 to 7,000  
visitors, is one of dozens being held this month at county 
fairgrounds and strip malls from Tacoma, Wash., to Watertown, N.Y. 
The shows, advertised in gun-store newsletters and Internet sites 
like www.shotgunnews.com and www.ak-47.net, draw aficionados from 
hundreds of miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	Many come for the deals. One Greensburg seller dropped his price  
on the Intratec AB-10 -- a legal version of the banned TEC-9 series 
-- from $249 to $209. 
</P>
<P>
	Others come because there's no other place to find such a broad  
array of collectibles: A $1,200 ``pre-ban'' AK-47 assault rifle. 
The armor-piercing bullets President Clinton wants to ban -- 40 
rounds for $15. Books on Daniel Boone and Thomas Jefferson. The 
World War II uniform of a Japanese naval aviator. A Union belt from 
the Civil War. A rifle stand painted with a red and black swastika 
bearing the misspelled German phrase ``Gott mitt uns'' -- God with 
us. 
</P>
<P>
	Many vendors sell large ammunition clips and assault weapons  
that were banned in 1994 but can be sold because of ``grandfather'' 
clauses in federal law. Among them are the TEC DC-9 and reloadable 
clips that hold as many as 40 bullets. The federal Brady bill 
banned the manufacture of clips holding more than 10. 
</P>
<P>
	But beyond firearms, the shows offer less tangible attractions.  
</P>
<P>
	``Friendship is what it's all about,'' said Marv Adams, who  
drove 250 miles from Perrysburg, Ohio, to show off a private 
collection that includes an 1887 rifle once owned by ``Buffalo'' 
Bill Cody, valued at $125,000. ``These are guys that collect. They 
come here and they talk guns. It's just a comradeship that we 
enjoy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adams, a white-haired insurance agent in a black blazer and  
white cowboy hat, has donated guns to the Smithsonian Institution 
and the National Rifle Association's firearms museum. He made $140 
in sales Saturday, less than he spent picking up collectibles. Most 
of the Howard Thunderbolts he sells cost about $3,000, well over 
the typical $250 to $500 gun show purchase. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most collectors don't come here for the money,'' he said. ``If  
I sold one of them I'd immediately go out and spend the money on 
things I collect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Greensburg show is what's known as a ``controlled show.''  
Armed guards man the doors. Agents from the Bureau of Alcohol, 
Tobacco and Firearms, here by invitation, field legal questions. 
Only sellers who have been vetted by the association can buy one of 
the $30 exhibit tables. A sign inside the door reads, ``Proper 
attire,'' meaning no white supremacist T-shirts -- and no trench 
coats. 
</P>
<P>
	But even controlled shows have their setbacks. At the March show  
a buyer was escorted out in handcuffs after police performing a 
background check turned up outstanding warrants. 
</P>
<P>
	Dealers are required to do a background check of all buyers.  
</P>
<P>
	``Selling guns is easy,'' said Rod Herrmann, director of the  
hosting association. ``It's the paperwork that's hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike many states, Pennsylvania requires even private  
collectors to do a background check of handgun buyers, which a 
dealer will perform for $5 to $10. But anyone can buy and sell 
rifles and shotguns without any paperwork. That is one of the 
loopholes the Senate bill approved Friday would close. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure isn't popular among gun enthusiasts.  
</P>
<P>
	``The girl who bought the guns in Colorado was legal whether she  
had a background check or not,'' said Phillips, owner of Bill's 
Guns in New Alexander, Pa., who sells two of the guns Littleton 
student Robyn Anderson allegedly bought for the Colorado gunmen at 
a gun show. 
</P>
<P>
	One of them, the Hi Point carbine, is a short-barreled military  
weapon designed to kill people. Pennsylvania law bars deer hunters 
from using it. But that's no reason to ban it, Phillips said. The 
Constitution's ``right to bear arms'' clause, he said, was written 
by revolutionaries eager to preserve the right of future 
generations to take up arms against people -- their oppressors. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Second Amendment isn't about hunting rights,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
