<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dumars Ends Career on Sour Note </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- It wasn't the way Joe Dumars wanted to end his  
career. 
</P>
<P>
	Dumars scored only three points in the final game of his 14-year  
career as the Atlanta Hawks beat his Detroit Pistons 87-75 in the 
decisive fifth game of opening round of the playoffs Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a fun year for me. I'm not going to make this a sad  
day at all. I'm disappointed (with the loss). I don't know what 
else to say,'' said Dumars, who got a hug from coach Alvin Gentry 
when he was taken out of the game with 51.9 seconds left. 
</P>
<P>
	And then Atlanta's entire starting five hugged the 36-year-old  
guard before Hawks' coach Lenny Wilkens ran to Detroit's bench and 
added a bear hug of his own. 
</P>
<P>
	``I appreciated that. Being on the road and having the road team  
show their appreciation like that was great,'' Dumars said. 
</P>
<P>
	``And, now it's over. I wish I could stand here and tell you I'm  
disappointed, I'm sad, I'm happy. I have all those emotions wrapped 
up in one,'' Dumars said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dumars averaged 16.1 points during his career -- all with the  
Pistons -- after being a No. 1 draft pick in 1985 out of McNeese 
State. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm disappointed we lost, but I'm more disappointed that this  
was Joe's last game,'' said teammate Grant Hill, who led the 
Pistons with 21 points. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's meant so much to me as a leader, a teammate and a friend.  
Hopefully, he'll still be there to give me advice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dumars, who played 32 minutes and made only one of his six  
shots, said he hoped he'll be remembered for his accomplishments 
and ``that I left with class.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That he did.  
</P>
<P>
	Dumars played in 10 playoffs, helping the Pistons to consecutive  
NBA titles in 1989 and 1990. In 1990, he was named the NBA Finals 
MVP after averaging 27.3 points in four-game sweep of the Los 
Angeles Lakers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now it's on to life after basketball. I'm going to enjoy  
myself. I've lived in Detroit 14 years now and it's my home. I 
intend to stay there,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll be going to all the games and be their biggest fan,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry Stackhouse, who played primarily as Dumars' backup this  
season and scored 11 points in 25 minutes against the Hawks, will 
get his chance to start next season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Joe's had an unbelievable career. I'm proud to say I played on  
the same team with him,'' said Stackhouse. ``I can tell my kids 
some day that I played with the legendary Joe Dumars.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
