<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 15:11:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cauthen Roots for Charismatic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Steve Cauthen, who rode the last Triple  
Crown winner 21 years ago, has climbed aboard the Charismatic 
bandwagon. 
</P>
<P>
	Cauthen says he'll root for the Kentucky Derby and Preakness  
winner to take the Belmont and become the 12th Triple Crown 
champion -- and the first since he and Affirmed outdueled Alydar and 
Jorge Velasquez in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's meant to happen, and if the whole thing falls  
together, it would be great,'' Cauthen said Sunday in a telephone 
interview from his home in Walton. ``Seeing stars being made -- and 
Charismatic would be a genuine thoroughbred star -- that's what 
racing needs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cauthen admits that Charismatic sneaked up on him with his  
longshot victory in the Derby. But the one-time teen riding 
sensation who now has his own breeding operation has gained a 
growing respect for the colt. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's dug in and worked hard to win his races, and looks like  
he may even have a little more left in the tank,'' Cauthen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cauthen was a mere 18 when he guided Affirmed to a Triple Crown  
sweep over archrival Alydar, culminated by a head victory as the 
two great rivals charged down the stretch in the Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each one got closer and more exciting, and the Belmont being  
the epitome of the way you'd love to win the race that was for 
everything, which it was,'' Cauthen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cauthen said it's difficult to predict how a 3-year-old  
thoroughbred will respond to the 1 1/2-mile distance of the Belmont. 
The Kentucky Derby is contested at 1 1/4 miles, the Preakness at 1 
3-16. 
</P>
<P>
	``A mile and a half is a different distance than they have ever  
run before, and probably ever will run again,'' he said. ``You 
never know until you get there. I didn't know with Affirmed until 
the day of the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cauthen praised jockey Chris Antley for his handling of  
Charismatic in the Derby and Preakness. He said all the attention 
before the Belmont and a possible Triple Crown can also be a 
jarring ride for a jockey. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure he'll give him a good ride in the Belmont,'' Cauthen  
said. ``I just know that the next three weeks are going to be awful 
tense for him. It's a long three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure once he gets on the horse on Belmont day, he'll be  
glad that he's ready to fire it and take his chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic is the seventh horse to complete the Derby-Preakness  
double since Affirmed. The other six colts came up short in the 
Belmont -- including Silver Charm in 1997 and Real Quiet in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a tough thing to pull off,'' Cauthen said. ``A horse has  
to be at 100 percent each time and you just can't afford anything 
to go wrong in between.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now retired from riding, Cauthen has moved on to other roles in  
the sport. He has a horse-breeding operation in northern Kentucky 
and is an executive at nearby Turfway Park. 
</P>
<P>
	He's also part owner of a filly sired by Affirmed. She was born  
just this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm excited about her,'' Cauthen said.  
</P>
<P>
	Cauthen reunited briefly with Affirmed for a ceremony at Jonabel  
Farm, marking the 20th anniversary of the horse's Triple Crown 
glory. Cauthen said Affirmed was ``looking like a teen-ager.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And though he's rooting for Charismatic, don't expect Cauthen to  
put this year's 3-year-old sensation in Affirmed's class. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't compare any horses to Affirmed because I think  
Affirmed was the best,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990516.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 17:11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New MBAs Flood Internet Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- At 30, Anne Stanton isn't a corporate titan. At  
least not yet. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 1999 graduate of Harvard Business School is forsaking  
job security and a fat paycheck for the potential for phenomenal 
wealth and success offered by an Internet startup she launched with 
classmates. 
</P>
<P>
	Among their peers in the newest class of Harvard MBAs, their  
gamble is not unique. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people that are on the team, they've turned down  
salaries of $150,000 and bonuses of $50,000,'' said Stanton, who 
hopes her company, LocalREWARDS.com, will be operating in 40 to 60 
markets by November. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of Harvard Business School graduates saying they plan  
to go into high-technology businesses or start their own businesses 
has been rising over the last few years, and the jump from 1998 to 
1999 has been especially robust, according to an informal student 
poll of about 45 percent of this year's students. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the poll, 8 percent of the class planned to become  
entrepreneurs, owners or partners in their first year out of 
school. That's up from just 3 percent recorded last year by the 
school's career services office. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, 25 percent expressed an interest in high-technology  
businesses, up from 11 percent last year and just 7 percent in 
1997, the student survey said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Stanton acknowledges that success as an online entrepreneur  
is not a sure thing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty much job insecurity every day until you prove in  
the real world that your numbers work,'' said Stanton, whose 
company works with local businesses on loyalty programs that reward 
customers for repeat business. 
</P>
<P>
	Harvard Business School graduates have always had an  
entrepreneurial streak, with about 40 percent launching their own 
ventures at some point in their careers. 
</P>
<P>
	But the MBAs traditionally apprenticed themselves first to firms  
in corporate America for five or 10 years, then went out on their 
own. 
</P>
<P>
	That's no longer the case.  
</P>
<P>
	Professors attribute the surge of entrepreneurship to a variety  
of factors, not the least of which are investors' enthusiasm for 
giving capital to new Internet companies and a lack of established 
power brokers blocking newcomers on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the Internet, there are no entrenched authorities. It's  
being invented as we go,'' said Michael J. Roberts, a professor of 
entrepreneurial management at Harvard. ``The other piece of the 
Internet equation is the capital ... People see how much money is 
out there to fund these ventures.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, PricewaterhouseCoopers released a study showing  
venture capital investments in Internet-related companies more than 
tripled from just over $1 billion in 312 firms around the country 
in 1996 to $3.5 billion in 641 companies last year. 
</P>
<P>
	But some of the new MBAs say they're most excited about building  
something new. 
</P>
<P>
	``Money's not the driving force behind it. We clearly could go  
places where we'd get paid more,'' said Asif Satchu, who is earning 
his MBA with Harvard's class of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	He passed up four job offers in the button-down worlds of  
private equity, consulting and investment banking to venture out 
into the raucous new field of Internet commerce. Now, he and a 
classmate are trying to wrap up financing on a new business, 
Suppliermarket.com, which is designed to help manufacturing 
companies manage their supply chains. 
</P>
<P>
	Graduates of Harvard's crosstown rival, the Sloan School of  
Management at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, have also 
taken advantage of the Internet boom. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems to be in the air,'' said Rob Carney, a 1999 MBA  
already working with a startup called Adero that helps companies do 
business on the Internet in foreign countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a lot more people are opting to go work for smaller  
startups, maybe for the excitement and the chance to build 
something. You have the change to contribute more,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
