<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GUADALAJARA, Mexico (AP) -- Army troops guarding evacuated  
villages on the flanks of the rumbling Colima volcano were 
withdrawn to a safer distance Sunday as concern grew among experts 
that another large eruption could occur. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of soldiers assigned to guard the empty houses in the  
villages of Yerba Buena in Colima state and Juan Barragan in 
Jalisco state were ordered to move further away, said Jaime Arturo 
Paz, Jalisco state civil defense spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 250 were evacuated May 10 from several hamlets near the  
volcano, 75 miles south of Guadalajara. It is considered one of 
Mexico's most dangerous volcano complexes. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Suspected leftist rebels kidnapped an  
American helicopter technician, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	The American was identified in an army press release as Matthew  
Buchell, a technical consultant for AIRlogistic, a helicopter firm 
that works with the British Petroleum oil company. 
</P>
<P>
	He was seized Saturday by five armed men while traveling by taxi  
to the airport in Yopal, capital of Casanare state. Yopal is 130 
miles northwest of Bogota. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Embassy in Bogota said it had no comment on the case.  
</P>
<P>
	The army blamed the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or  
FARC, which operates in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	The 15,000-strong rebel group, and the smaller National  
Liberation Army, ELN, rely on kidnapping and extortion to fund 
their war against the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
