<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rubin Replacment: Strong Dollar Key </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANGKAWI, Malaysia (AP) -- A strong dollar is in the United  
States' national interest, U.S. Treasury Secretary-designate 
Lawrence Summers said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Secretary Rubin and I have seen this the same way for many  
years,'' he said. ``A strong dollar is very much in America's 
national interest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This is the first time Summers has commented on the dollar since  
he was nominated for the post of treasury secretary. Last week, 
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin submitted his resignation. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers made his remarks following a weekend gathering of  
Asia-Pacific finance ministers. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers said that a strong dollar benefits the United States by  
helping lower inflation and trade income. 
</P>
<P>
	``Experience suggests that nations can't devalue their way to  
prosperity,'' he added, referring to pressures to allow a lower 
currency to boost exports. ``The dollar should not be used as a 
tool of trade policy.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
