<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bad Men Featured in Cannes Movies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANNES, France (AP) -- They're scared, weak, mean or unreliable.  
They're neurotic, hypochondriacal, tyrannical or just plain stupid. 
</P>
<P>
	We're talking about men -- more specifically, male characters in  
films at Cannes this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The 52nd annual festival isn't yet halfway through, so it's  
early to declare a trend. But judging from films in competition so 
far, it isn't looking good for the Y chromosome. 
</P>
<P>
	Take the film that's generated the best buzz so far: ``All About  
My Mother,'' by Spanish director Pedro Almodovar. There's a reason 
it isn't called ``All About My Father'' -- the dad in question has 
become a transvestite called Lola and left the family unit. 
</P>
<P>
	The mother, Manuela, is a strong, decent woman. A nurse, she  
appears in instructional videos on organ transplants, playing the 
wife who must sign a consent form donating her husband's organs. 
</P>
<P>
	In a melodramatic twist typical of Almodovar, Manuela takes her  
17-year-old son to the theater for his birthday, then sees him run 
over by a car as he chases an actress for her autograph. Soon, it 
is Manuela who must sign the same dreadful consent form. 
</P>
<P>
	We follow Manuela from Madrid to Barcelona, where she hooks up  
with three other women, all with huge problems of their own. The 
always-fascinating Almodovar, aided by great acting, focuses 
successfully on their resilience and humor. Nowhere is a good man 
to be found. 
</P>
<P>
	Another promising film was ``Wonderland,'' by British director  
Michael Winterbottom. It, too, looks at a group of women -- three 
sisters -- and their troubled search for happiness, focused on one 
long weekend in London. 
</P>
<P>
	Nadia looks for dates through singles ads. One is so unappealing  
that Nadia needs to sneak out of the bar; another raises her hopes, 
then seduces her and moves on. 
</P>
<P>
	Her sister, Molly, is about to give birth when her husband  
panics, quits his job and disappears, leaving her to go through 
labor and childbirth alone. And Debbie, the other sister, is 
raising an 11-year-old son alone. Her irresponsible ex-husband asks 
for money and loses the boy in an amusement park. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there was ``Kadosh,'' an Israeli film about ultra-Orthodox  
Jews that depicts their lives as bleak and restrictive -- and 
nightmarish for the women. Two sisters, Rivka and Malka, experience 
loneliness, rejection, physical pain and worse. 
</P>
<P>
	All, of course, at the hands of the men in their lives and in  
their community, the ultra-Orthodox neighborhood of Mea Shearim in 
Jerusalem, where marriages are arranged, sex is for procreation 
only and a sterile woman is cast off. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, there was the German film ``Moloch,'' directed by a  
Russian, Alexander Sokourov. In this movie there is no argument 
about the quality of the lead male character: He is Adolf Hitler. 
</P>
<P>
	Needless to say, Hitler is presented here with all the qualities  
he is known for, and then some. The film depicts his relationship 
with young Eva Braun. With her, he is tyrannical, irrational, a 
hypochondriac and lots of other unappealing things. 
</P>
<P>
	To be fair, Eva is no picnic, either, and for that matter  
neither is the film; many left a press screening early to escape 
the tedium. 
</P>
<P>
	With all these depressing characters, it was a relief to see  
Sean Connery drop into the festival to promote his new film, 
``Entrapment,'' out of competition. As the cheering crowds 
affirmed, the original James Bond is still looking pretty good. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990516.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 14:01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rubin Sees Economy Still Strong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Departing Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin on  
Sunday said a Republican push for a major tax cut could sidetrack 
the nation from what he predicted would be sustained economic 
growth and low inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin, who will step down in July, said the budget surplus gives  
the nation a ``historic opportunity'' to ensure the long-term U.S. 
economic health. 
</P>
<P>
	``If instead we have a broad-based tax cut, we can consume that  
surplus ... (and) throw away an enormous opportunity to promote our 
economic well-being for a long time to come,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	With budget surpluses expected to continue into the foreseeable  
future, Republicans want to set aside $1.8 trillion in Social 
Security surpluses over the next decade to save the retirement 
system and use the rest, some $778 billion, for tax cuts. The 
administration has proposed much smaller and targeted tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Does the country, Rubin asked on ABC's ``This Week,'' ``in  
effect institutionalize fiscal discipline by paying down public 
debt, or do we in effect dissipate those surpluses on broad-based 
tax cuts?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin praised President Clinton for sticking to a strong fiscal  
policy ``from the day he walked into the Oval office.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said he was unfazed by a jump in the consumer price index  
that caused a dip in the stock market Friday. The most likely 
scenario for the future, he said, remains one of solid growth and 
low inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the world economy remains in a ``very unhealthy  
situation'' with the United States the only major economy with 
robust growth, Rubin said. ``Most particularly it is critically 
important that Japan get back on track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin, who oversaw one of the longest periods of sustained  
economic growth in the nation's history, is returning to New York, 
where he was chairman of Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co., before he succeeded 
Lloyd Bentsen as Treasury secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has nominated Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers  
to take over the post. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said he thought about resigning last year, ``but we had an  
awful lot going on,'' including a world financial crisis sparked by 
turmoil in Asia, and the Monica Lewinsky affair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
