<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Star Emerging in Indy Racing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- With Arie Luyendyk retiring and Tony Stewart  
driving in NASCAR, the name-starved Indy Racing League is looking 
for a new hero. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Ray, a 32-year-old who never has won a race, might be the  
personality the 4-year-old Indy-car series needs to make new fans 
and carve some inroads into NASCAR's burgeoning popularity. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray, with movie star looks and an articulate manner, also has  
proven to be fast on the race track. He started second in last 
year's Indianapolis 500 and has started from the front row in both 
races this season, going from No. 2 in Orlando and winning his 
first career pole in Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	His best finish so far, though, was second in the race at Texas  
Motor Speedway last June while still running for the underfunded 
team of Thomas Knapp, a close friend and now his engineer. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Ray is among the favorites to win May 30 in the 83rd  
running of the Indy 500, thanks to his move into the seat at Team 
Menard left vacant when 1997 series champion Stewart moved 
full-time to the Winston Cup series this season. 
</P>
<P>
	That has given lots of confidence to Ray, who has been fastest  
on each of the first two days of practice at the Indianapolis Motor 
Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday, Ray's fast lap was 225.887 mph. Sunday, the cool Texan  
led the way in his primary car at 225.124 and was third in his 
backup Dallara-Aurora at 224.674. 
</P>
<P>
	``My confidence is changing,'' Ray said. ``Last year, we knew  
there were holes in our arsenal. We didn't have the countermeasures 
and insurance measures built into our program. We were fast, but we 
just didn't have the backup plan, the backup people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He pointed to the fact that John Menard's team has won races and  
a championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're a championship team, you have things built into  
your arsenal to deal with problems,'' Ray said. ``The key thing 
with a team like this is there are some very good people around 
you. ... We also have good chemistry. You can trust everybody. You 
can count on everybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite all that chemistry, isn't the winless Ray at least a  
little uncomfortable in the role of favorite at Indy? 
</P>
<P>
	``My dad disagreed with me in 1997 when I first showed up here  
for my first Indy 500 and thought that I was the favorite to win 
the race,'' Ray said, smiling. ``I don't want anybody to take this 
the wrong way. I have high expectations of myself. I've never been 
in a race car not expecting to win. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no fifth or 10th. Racing is about winning. That is why  
I got involved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forty cars made laps Sunday on the 2 1/2-mile oval, with two-time  
Indy winner Luyendyk sandwiched between Ray's cars at 224.674. 
Two-time runner-up Scott Goodyear was next at 222.750, followed by 
defending IRL champion Kenny Brack and former series champion Scott 
Sharp, both at 222.288. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, who plans to race in both the Indy 500 and the  
Coca-Cola 600 at Charlotte, N.C., May 30, arrived Sunday after 
finishing 15th in a Winston Cup race Saturday night at Richmond, 
Va. 
</P>
<P>
	He quickly got up to speed in his new Tri Star Motorsports  
entry, turning a fast lap of 222.091. 
</P>
<P>
	Billy Boat, last year's pole winner, was the first to hit the  
wall since practice opened Saturday. Brack's A.J. Foyt Racing 
teammate lost control exiting turn one and skidded backward into 
the concrete barrier. 

</P>
</TEXT>
