<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smart Car May Lose Funding Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAMBURG, Germany (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler chief Juergen Schremp  
has threatened to cut investment in the mini Smart car if sales do 
not improve within six months, a newsmagazine reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Schremp, as quoted by the Der Spiegel report, said he would  
``turn off the money tap'' if he does not see a dramatic climb in 
orders for the cartoonish, two-seater car, which is built at a 
plant in Hambach, France. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler, which invested $1.1 billion in developing the  
Smart model, stands to lose an additional $1.1 billion to $1.6 
billion if the car fails, the magazine reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Although production was geared toward selling 140,000 Smart  
models this year, Schremp said the goal is now to sell 80,000 cars 
-- or else the project will have to be reconsidered, according to 
Der Spiegel. 
</P>
<P>
	Daimler already has changed management of the Smart unit,  
lowered prices and launched a sweeping ad campaign to improve 
sales, the magazine said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Smart car, which went on sale across Europe on Oct. 2, was  
developed by Micro Compact Car AG, a joint venture between 
Daimler-Benz and Swatch Group, the Swiss manufacturer of the Swatch 
wristwatch. In November, Swatch sold its stake in the project to 
Daimler. 
</P>
<P>
	The 8.25-foot-long car takes up just about half of a standard  
parking spot and runs on around a third less gas than its compact 
rivals. With its mix-and-match, brightly colored replaceable parts 
and all-plastic body, the car is aimed at a young market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
