<HEADLINE> 'Mummy' Hangs On to Top Spot / Box Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``The Mummy'' held on to No. 1 at the box  
office over the weekend, earning $25.1 million, according to 
industry estimates released Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The weekend was considered a wasteland by most studio  
executives, who feared moviegoers would hold off in anticipation of 
``Star Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom Menace.'' The film opens 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	That may account for the unusually high number of smaller films  
in the top 10, according to Robert Bucksbaum, a Reel Source Inc. 
film analyst. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't usually want to open a film five days before the  
most anticipated film of the decade, and perhaps of all time,'' 
Bucksbaum said. ``When you do, you're either hoping to get 
spillover audience from the sold-out 'Star Wars' shows, or you're 
trying to appeal to a totally different audience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The Mummy,'' a horror-adventure film about a group of  
explorers who accidentally resurrect an ancient Egyptian priest has 
become the season's biggest moneymaker, taking in $80.8 million 
since its release two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The cat-burglar caper ``Entrapment'' was No. 2 with $8.7 million  
in weekend earnings, while ``The Matrix'' was third with $4.5 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	``William Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream,'' starring  
Kevin Kline, Michelle Pfeiffer, Stanley Tucci and Calista 
Flockhart, opened this week in fourth place with $4.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Black Mask,'' a Hong Kong martial arts thriller, opened in  
fifth place with $4.2 million. It stars Jet Li as a mild-mannered 
librarian who becomes a masked crimefighter. 
</P>
<P>
	The urban comedy ``Trippin','' about a rambunctious teen-age  
daydreamer, debuted in seventh place with $2.6 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In limited release, ``Tea With Mussolini,'' the story of a boy  
raised by eccentric Englishwomen in World War II Italy, landed in 
10th place. The film, showing in 270 theaters, earned a per-screen 
average of $6,296. 
</P>
<P>
	Estimated grosses for Friday through Sunday at North American  
theaters, according to Exhibitor Relations Inc., with final figures 
to be released Monday: 
</P>
<P>
	1. ``The Mummy,'' $25.1 million.  
</P>
<P>
	2. ``Entrapment,'' $8.7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	3. ``The Matrix,'' $4.5 million.  
</P>
<P>
	4. ``William Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream,'' $4.4  
million. 
</P>
<P>
	5. ``Black Mask,'' $4.2 million.  
</P>
<P>
	6. ``Life,'' $2.9 million.  
</P>
<P>
	7. ``Trippin','' $2.6 million.  
</P>
<P>
	8. ``Never Been Kissed,'' $2.45 million.  
</P>
<P>
	9. ``Election,'' $2.3 million.  
</P>
<P>
	10. ``Tea With Mussolini,'' $1.7 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
