<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Calls for New Teacher Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAMONI, Iowa (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore called for tough new  
teacher tests, recruiting bonuses of up to $10,000 and 
``second-chance schools'' as he began Sunday to detail his agenda 
for his White House bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore used a commencement speech at Graceland College for the  
first in a series of public policy addresses he said would bring 
substance to his campaign for the Democratic nomination for 
president in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	He urged the hiring of 2.2 million new teachers, while making  
them pass tough tests, and said preschool programs should be 
extended ``for every child, in every community in America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A new ``teacher corps'' could offer youngsters up to $10,000 if  
they decide to go college to become a teacher, and a $10,000 bonus 
could await those who switch from other professions, Gore 
suggested. States would be encouraged to toughen teacher licensing. 
</P>
<P>
	Also needed are expanded after-school programs and more choices  
for parents within the public school system, the vice president 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Gore nor aides would say how much his proposals might  
cost. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is an agenda that is ambitious but responsible,'' Gore  
said. ``Every one of these proposals will be fully paid for within 
a balanced budget.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added: ``We must realize that education is the greatest  
anti-poverty program, the most powerful anti-discrimination 
strategy we could ever have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In light of the recent school shootings in Littleton, Colo.,  
Gore stressed school safety, promoting special ``second-chance'' 
programs for troubled youngsters. He also favored expanded family 
leave laws so parents could become more involved in their 
children's education. 
</P>
<P>
	Also part of his educational proposals:  
</P>
<P>
	-- More control for local school officials over staff, budget and  
student advancement. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Programs to identify ``failing schools'' and give parents more  
leeway in putting their children in different schools. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Wiring every classroom and library to the Internet and  
improving software. 
</P>
<P>
	-- New savings accounts allowing parents to save money for  
college expenses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
