<DOCNO> APW19990516.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 09:21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Injured Agassi May Miss French Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUESSELDORF, Germany (AP) -- Andre Agassi injured a shoulder  
Sunday during the World Team Cup, jeopardizing his start for the 
French Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very serious injury,'' said Halmut Krahl, the  
tournament doctor who examined Agassi and will treat him the next 
few days. 
</P>
<P>
	Agassi's bursitis flared while trailing 4-3 in the first set,  
and he was forced to quit. He was playing Nicolas Escude during the 
United States' match against France. 
</P>
<P>
	Agassi will skip the rest of the team tournament, a clay-court  
warmup for the French Open, which begins May 24. 
</P>
<P>
	``The cold and the heavy balls are too dangerous for my  
shoulder,'' Agassi said. ``I don't want to risk my small chance of 
playing in the French Open.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The same injury forced Agassi into a one-month layoff after he  
won a tournament in Hong Kong in April and caused him to withdraw 
at Monte Carlo three weeks ago.. 
</P>
<P>
	He returned at last week's Italian Open, where he was beaten by  
Australia's Pat Rafter. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States won its opening match 2-1 as Pete Sampras beat  
Cedric Pioline 7-5, 6-4 and Richey Reneberg and Jonathan Stark 
defeated Guillaume Raoux and Pioline 6-2, 6-4. 
</P>
<P>
	After his victory, Sampras felt confident about the French Open,  
despite recently losing his world No. 1 ranking to Russia's Yevgeny 
Kafelnikov. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've learned a lot in the last weeks and months, especially,  
that you only play good when you play a lot,'' said Sampras, who 
skipped the Australian Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was good for my private life, less so for my tennis. But I  
was beginning to feel like a robot, that without thinking, kept 
hitting a tennis ball.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
