<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 22:21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Help for Cotton This Year / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Cotton farmer Pat Pacheco got an eerie feeling  
when he finished planting his 1,800-acre field in Marana, Ariz., 
last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know, maybe I should have planted wheat instead,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pacheco's worries stem from the dropping price of Arizona's top  
cash crop. Because of economic problems in Asia and a large 
surplus, prices have dropped to half what his father made for 
cotton in the 1950s. 
</P>
<P>
	Especially troubling for farmers like Pacheco is that for the  
first time in eight years, American cotton growers won't have 
federal dollars to help them export crops worldwide, said Wayne 
Bjorlie of the U.S. Farm Service Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The result? When Pacheco harvests his cotton this winter, he  
might not be able to compete with cheaper cotton overseas. This 
would make the surplus rise and prices slump even more. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure if we're in a crisis situation now, but there  
will be one in the future if something doesn't happen soon,'' said 
Wiley Murphy, president of the Arizona Cotton Growers Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Cotton -- one of the Arizona's five C's along with copper,  
citrus, climate and cattle -- is the state's biggest agricultural 
crop. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Arizona farmers produced 888,800 bales of cotton worth  
$286 million. Much of this has been for export to such countries as 
Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1991, the federal government has helped cotton farmers  
compete with lower prices in other countries by paying exporters to 
buy U.S. cotton. In 1996, Congress capped these export incentives 
to $701 million -- enough money, lawmakers thought, to last until 
2002. 
</P>
<P>
	But international cotton prices have slumped so low that the  
money ran out last December. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because we're exporting to foreign markets, every farmer is  
hurting,'' said Lloyd Brown, a spokesman for the state Department 
of Agriculture. ``There are some fruit and vegetable growers that 
are doing well, but most are doing badly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This leaves farmers with few options, Brown said. They could try  
raising pigs or planting wheat instead of cotton. But nothing is 
going to make them much more money. 
</P>
<P>
	Every Arizona cotton farm is in jeopardy, Murphy said. At 55 to  
65 cents per pound, farmers can't make enough to pay for fuel or 
finance their farms. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I'm crazy for planting cotton right now,'' said Murphy,  
who owns 600 acres of cotton fields in Marana. ``You need to get at 
least 70 cents per pound to make ends meet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) -- Take me out to the ballgame, buy me some  
peanuts and Cracker Jack. 
</P>
<P>
	Or how about a DunkApple?  
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Apple Commission has signed a contract with the  
Seattle Mariners to sell DunkApples -- sliced apples served with 
tubs of caramel -- when the new Safeco Field opens in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Growers are hoping to develop sports fans as a new market for  
apples. Eventually, the commission would like to introduce 
DunkApples at stadiums around the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing like it in the ball park. You're looking at  
chips, hot dogs and nachos,'' said Kevin Bredesen, the commission's 
director of food service marketing in Wenatchee. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission has been looking for ways to increase domestic  
consumption of apples, a crop getting bigger in this state. Last 
year, Washington growers harvested 100 million 43-pound boxes. 
</P>
<P>
	DunkApples will sell for $2 to $3. The contracts with the  
Mariners and the team's concessionaire, Volume Services America, 
take effect in July and extend through the 2000 season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
