<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Smokestacks' Rise on Wall Street / Ticker Talk  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Forget high technology for the moment -- Wall  
Street is bullish on old-fashioned smokestack America. 
</P>
<P>
	In the latest bull-market surge this spring, the spotlight has  
shifted away from computers, the Internet and health-care 
innovation to more basic businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``The nation's cyclical manufacturing sector -- the companies  
that produce the nuts and bolts of the American economy such as 
paper, chemicals and primary metals -- may very well be 
rebounding,'' says Robert Kearns at the investment management firm 
of David L. Babson &AMP; Co. in Cambridge, Mass. ``The U.S. economy, 
now in its eighth year of expansive growth, may still have a good 
deal more life left in it than anyone expected only a few months 
ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nobody suggests that the technology boom is over, or that stock  
traders have suddenly turned nostalgic for the low-tech days of 
yore. 
</P>
<P>
	``No industry is more important to investors than technology,''  
say analysts at the investment newsletter Dow Theory Forecasts in 
Hammond, Ind. ``That fact is unlikely to change anytime soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``Still, technology shares can become overvalued. Part of what  
defines a bull market is an ability to undergo industry-group 
corrections without a major breakdown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The newsletter points out that in the Dow Jones industrial  
average's rise from 9,000 to 10,000, ``just six stocks -- IBM, 
Wal-Mart Stores, United Technologies, Merck, McDonald's, and 
General Electric -- accounted for most of the move.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But in the average's subsequent climb from 10,000 in March to  
11,000 less than two months later, more than two-thirds of the 30 
Dow components contributed, ``including double-digit gains in such 
cyclical names as Alco, AlliedSignal, International Paper, DuPont 
and Minnesota Mining,'' Dow Theory Forecasts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Recently the Dow Jones average of 20 transportation stocks  
joined the industrial average at a record high. Under the so-called 
Dow theory, simultaneous new highs in the two averages ``confirm'' 
that the rising trend of stock prices is intact. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are now finally indications that the U.S. manufacturing  
downturn that began in August 1997, when the Asian contagion began 
to put a damper on U.S. exports, may be on the upturn,'' ys Kearns. 
</P>
<P>
	Adds Joseph Battipaglia, investment policy chairman at the  
brokerage firm of Gruntal &AMP; Co. in New York: ``In April we saw 
renewed signs of strength in the economy and continued improvements 
in reported earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Industrial production numbers and the survey of purchasing  
managers both indicated that the sagging industrial sector may be 
nearing the end of its down cycle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As impressive as the recent show of strength by cyclical stocks  
may have been, however, many analysts question how long it will 
continue. Bullishness on the smokestack industries could quickly 
fade if the Federal Reserve shows any inclination to tighten credit 
conditions, either at this coming week's policy-setting meetings or 
sometime later in the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The markets were unsettled Friday morning when the April data on  
inflation showed a larger-than-expected 0.7 percent jump in the 
consumer price index. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Fed isn't expected to do anything dramatic on the  
basis of one monthly number, analysts note that bond-market 
interest rates have lately moved up to their highest levels in 
almost a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Federal Reserve, while impressed by low inflation, will  
obviously not sit still indefinitely if the economy keeps moving at 
this pace,'' says Richard Rippe, director of the economics research 
group at Prudential Securities. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
