<HEADLINE> New Treasury Heads Meets Japanese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANGKAWI, Malaysia (AP) -- For participants in the latest meeting  
between the top financial officials of Japan and the United States, 
it was business as usual despite the news that Lawrence Summers 
will soon become U.S. Treasury Secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	With the U.S. administration keen to emphasize policy continuity  
with Summers' elevation to replace Robert Rubin in Treasury's top 
job, Summers himself was at pains to present a cooperative face at 
his first bilateral meeting since Wednesday's announcement. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, a senior Japanese Finance Ministry official went out of  
his way to portray the meeting between Japanese Finance Minister 
Kiichi Miyazawa and Summers as amicable and deferential. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers ``didn't request anything specific regarding the  
Japanese economy, but rather asked Minister Miyazawa how (the 
economy) was doing, and didn't say anything else,'' the official 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese financial markets had looked forward to the meeting on  
the sidelines of the finance ministers' meeting of the Asia-Pacific 
Economic Cooperation forum to gauge whether Summers would be more 
aggressive than Rubin in calling for new stimulus measures in 
Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers and Miyazawa ``reviewed the situation in their  
respective economies'' and they agreed that ``Japan would continue 
its efforts to strengthen its economy and financial system until 
growth is restored and implement structural reform to enhance the 
economy's efficiency and competition,'' a spokeswoman for the U.S. 
Treasury told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers' low-key approach to the meeting with Miyazawa is more  
likely a reflection of the deputy secretary's delicate political 
standing than a sign that he is adopting a more passive tone with 
the Japanese. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Senate must vote on the White House's nomination of  
Summers to the top job, and the former Harvard professor is 
unlikely to prejudice the ticklish process with any remarks that 
might be used against him. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, Summers had repeatedly said that the United States  
can't be expected to remain a single engine of growth for the 
global economy. Treasury officials are advocating that Tokyo use 
all policy tools at its disposal get the Japanese economy back on 
track. 
</P>
</TEXT>
