<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Bombing in Kosovo Continues  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO warplanes bombarded Kosovo  
today, and the alliance expressed increasing suspicion that Serb 
forces had deliberately trapped civilians next to a military 
command post where 87 were reported killed by allied missiles. 
Yugoslavia protested that the intensive bombing is obstructing a 
partial withdrawal of its troops from Kosovo -- a complaint NATO 
spokesman Jamie Shea dismissed. A team of 15 U.N. officials is 
preparing to tour war damage in Kosovo and meet with Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic tomorrow morning. 

</P>
<P>
	Vietnam Compares Kosovo to Itself  
</P>
<P>
	HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- The North Vietnamese who helped build the  
Ho Chi Minh Trail, the supply-line route that kept their army 
supplied while withstanding heavy U.S. bombing, are cautioning the 
U.S. about its inablity to win in Yugoslavia. ``I think it's not a 
good idea to get involved in the Balkans,'' Maj. Gen. Do Xuan Dien 
told The Associated Press. ``Based on my 11 years of experience on 
the Ho Chi Minh Trail, you cannot win a war using only air power,'' 
Dien said. ``But if they use ground troops, they should be very 
careful because of the skills of the Serb soldiers.'' 

</P>
<P>
	FBI Reports Drop in Crime Last Year  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Preliminary figures from the FBI indicate a  
decline in serious crime for the seventh consecutive year, the 
Justice Department said today. Raw statistics for 1998 show a 7 
percent decline from the number of violent crimes and property 
offenses reported in 1997. Decreases were reported across the board 
in both violent crimes -- murder, rape, robbery and aggravated 
assault -- and property offenses -- burglary, larceny-theft, motor 
vehicle theft and arson, Justice officials said. Robberies fell 11 
percent and vehicle thefts dropped 10 percent from 1997 levels, 
leading the way. The number of murders declined 8 percent, while 
rape and aggravated assaults both were down by 5 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Dozens Killed in Blast in Pakistan  
</P>
<P>
	ADDA RODU SULTAN, Pakistan (AP) -- An overturned truck loaded  
with gasoline exploded in Pakistan today as dozens of people were 
collecting fuel from the leaking tanker. As many as 65 people were 
killed and at least 75 others were injured, police said. Fire 
spread rapidly through the dusty town of Adda Rodu Sultan in 
eastern Punjab province, engulfing shops and homes, and sending 
giant plumes of smoke and flames into the sky. People with their 
clothes on fire jumped into a nearby canal. It was not clear what 
sparked the explosion, police said. 

</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu Faces Barak in Israel  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- The night before the election, the race for  
Prime Minister of Israel has narrowed to two candidates: 
beleaguered Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu against Ehud Barak, 
who is likely to revive peacemaking efforts with Palestinians. With 
the last two minor candidates dropping out today, the contest will 
be settled in a single ballot tomorrow. Netanyahu had hoped to push 
the race into a runoff, giving him two more weeks to campaign. The 
latest polls give Barak a solid lead. Pre-eminent pollster Hanoch 
Smith, in a survey conducted for tomorrow's newspapers, put Barak's 
lead at 8 to 10 percentage points, with a margin of error of 3 
percentage points. 

</P>
<P>
	Mexico Boat Blamed in Reef Damage  
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A shrimp boat whose engines stalled in bad  
weather has been blamed for damaging 1,290 square yards of coral, 
one of the worst cases of damage to Mexican reefs in recent memory. 
The boat ground through coral in shallow waters that are off-limits 
to marine traffic near the beach resort Cancun, 800 miles east of 
Mexico City, local media reported today. Environmental authorities 
were searching for the boat, whose owners may be liable for fines 
of up to $65,000 and could be forced to pay as much as $1.5 million 
to offset damage to the reef if they are found responsible. 

</P>
<P>
	Bruins Over Sabres, 5-3  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Don Sweeney beat Dominik Hasek 9:01 into the game  
to break a 116-minute shutout streak, and the Bruins scored three 
more times off Hasek in the second period to beat Buffalo 5-3 today 
in Game 5 of their Eastern Conference semifinal series. The Sabres 
lead three games to two with a chance to clinch the series in Game 
6 Tuesday night in Buffalo. In 18 tries, the Bruins have never won 
a playoff series after falling behind 3-1. 

</P>
<P>
	Knicks Move Into Second Round  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Allan Houston sank a last-second, 14-foot shot as  
the New York Knicks beat Miami 78-77 to move into the second round 
of the NBA playoffs. The Knicks became just the second 
eighth-seeded team in NBA history to defeat a No. 1 seed. They also 
may have saved the job of coach Jeff Van Gundy, who was expected to 
be fired if the Knicks lost. Instead, they'll go into the second 
round against the winner of the Detroit-Atlanta series. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
