<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Method Treats Cancer Spread </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- A new way of delivering chemotherapy appears to  
substantially improve the survival of people being treated for 
colon and rectal cancer that has spread to the liver. 
</P>
<P>
	The treatment involves injecting standard chemotherapy drugs  
directly into the hepatic artery, which supplies blood to the 
liver, rather than the usual method of putting the drugs into a 
vein. 
</P>
<P>
	About 138,000 new cases of colon and rectal cancer are diagnosed  
in the United States annually. Eventually, the disease spreads to 
the liver in about 60 percent of these people, and the outlook is 
grim. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Nancy Kemeny and colleagues from Memorial Sloan-Kettering  
Cancer Center in New York City tested the new way of giving 
chemotherapy in 156 patients. After surgery to remove the cancer 
from the liver, they were randomly assigned to get standard 
chemotherapy or the hepatic artery approach. 
</P>
<P>
	After two years, 85 percent of those getting arterial  
chemotherapy were still alive, compared with 69 percent receiving 
the drugs through a vein. Whether this will eventually translate 
into longer survival is unknown. However, Kemeny said projections 
suggest that 60 percent of those getting the arterial treatment 
will still be alive after five years, compared with 40 percent 
getting standard treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Kemeny presented the results Sunday at a meeting in Atlanta of  
the American Society of Clinical Oncology. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very elegant study and an important one,'' said Dr.  
Derek Raghaven of the University of Southern California. ``This is 
progress.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
