<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Serb POWs May Be Freed Soon  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The two Serb soldiers held as prisoners of war  
by U.S. military authorities in Germany will be released, possibly 
tomorrow, a senior Pentagon official said today. ``They are going 
to be released,'' the official said, speaking on condition of 
anonymity. ``We're just working out the details now.'' Defense 
Secretary William Cohen strongly hinted a few weeks ago that there 
was a good possibility the prisoners would be released, but there 
has been little word on their fate since then. The pending release 
of the Serb soldiers comes after the release earlier this month of 
three U.S. Army soldiers captured along the Kosovo-Macedonia 
border. 

</P>
<P>
	Serbs Take Border Crossings  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- As NATO warplanes continue  
bombarding Kosovo today, the Yugoslav army took control of border 
crossings out of Montenegro, Yugoslavia's junior republic. 
Residents in Montenegro have feared a Belgrade-led action against 
the republic's government, which has followed a pro-Western policy. 
Montenegrin officials said federal troops stopped Kosovo refugees 
trying to leave Montenegro for Albania. Soldiers separated men from 
the group and took them away, officials said. 

</P>
<P>
	FBI Reports Drop in Crime Last Year  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- There was a decline in serious crime for the  
seventh year in a row according to 1998's preliminary figures from 
the FBI, the Justice Department said today. Raw statistics for 1998 
show a 7 percent decline from the number of violent crimes and 
property offenses reported in 1997. Decreases were reported across 
the board in both violent crimes -- murder, rape, robbery and 
aggravated assault -- and property offenses -- burglary, 
larceny-theft, motor vehicle theft and arson, Justice officials 
said. The number of murders declined 8 percent, while rape and 
aggravated assaults both were down by 5 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Dozens Killed in Blast in Pakistan  
</P>
<P>
	ADDA RODU SULTAN, Pakistan (AP) -- An overturned truck loaded  
with gasoline exploded in Pakistan today as dozens of people were 
collecting fuel from the leaking tanker. As many as 65 people were 
killed and at least 75 others were injured, police said. Fire 
spread rapidly through the dusty town of Adda Rodu Sultan in 
eastern Punjab province, engulfing shops and homes, and sending 
giant plumes of smoke and flames into the sky. People with their 
clothes on fire jumped into a nearby canal. It was not clear what 
sparked the explosion, police said. 

</P>
<P>
	Israelis Fly Home To Vote  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- More than 2,000 people -- many of them Orthodox  
Jews -- took chartered flights from New York to Israel today to vote 
in that country's election for prime minister. Friedman Jacob and 
Joseph Weiss, both from New York, had Benjamin Netanyahu stickers 
on their luggage and held up an Israeli newspaper with the prime 
minister's picture. ``Bibi -- he's our leader,'' said Weiss. 
Netanyahu, the Likud or right-wing candidate, is trailing in the 
polls behind Ehud Barak, the Labor or left-wing candidate. The 
election takes place tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	Time: Suharto Amassed $15B Fortune  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Former Indonesian President Suharto and his six  
children amassed a $15 billion fortune during his 32 years in 
power, Time magazine says. The Suharto family has vast stores of 
cash, shares, corporate assets, real estate, jewelry and fine art, 
the magazine reports in its latest issue, which hits newsstands 
tomorrow. A press release from Time said Suharto's wealth was 
tallied in a four-month investigation covering 11 countries. 

</P>
<P>
	Forbes: 14 Baseball Teams in Red  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Fourteen of the 30 major league baseball teams  
posted operating losses last year, Forbes magazine reported today. 
The Los Angeles Dodgers lost money -- $11.7 million on an estimated 
$108 million in revenue -- in large part because of baseball's 
revenue-sharing system, which has baseball's top 13 
revenue-generating teams contributing $100 million to the 15 teams 
with the lowest revenues. That didn't stop the New York Yankees, 
which had to pay $13 million in revenue sharing, maintaining a 
value of $491 million, the best in baseball. 

</P>
<P>
	Roberts Wins Nelson Classic  
</P>
<P>
	IRVING, Texas (AP) -- Loren Roberts beat Steve Pate on the first  
sudden-death playoff hole today to win the Byron Nelson Classic. 
Roberts won $540,000 for his first victory in two years. Pate was 
the runner-up for the second time this year. Sergio Garcia, the 
19-year-old Spanish sensation, birdied the 18th for a 69 that left 
him tied for third at 269 along with Lee Janzen, Brian Watts and 
Chris DiMarco. Tiger Woods finished at 271, having played the final 
three rounds at even-par after opening with a 61. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
