<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Britain: Serbs Using Human Shields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Britain said Sunday it did not yet know why ethnic  
Albanian civilians were in a Kosovo village attacked by NATO, but 
that Serb police reportedly herded them there from their hiding 
places in the hills. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Thursday's attack on Korisa, which killed 87 civilians,  
NATO has suggested that they were used as human shields but has 
been unable to confirm that. 
</P>
<P>
	British Ministry of Defense spokesman John Spellar told  
reporters on Sunday that Korisa was a legitimate military target. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe it was being used as a military camp and command  
post with military vehicles and artillery present,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not yet know the reason why civilians were at this  
location at the time of the attack. But it increasingly appears 
likely, however, that the civilians were used as human shields. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're aware of continued reports that according to survivors,  
the civilians were ordered by Serb police to return to the village 
from the hills where they'd been hiding for several weeks,'' 
Spellar said. ``On their return they were not permitted to live in 
their homes, instead they were herded into concentrated areas 
within the village and held there until the NATO attack took 
place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said in Brussels that the forces of  
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic used human shields. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know that we're up against an adversary who has no scruples  
when it comes to using civilians as human shields,'' Shea said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Human shields are a factor, but they're not obviously going to  
stop us continue this air operation,'' Shea said, adding, ``we will 
never, never intentionally target civilians.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
