<DOCNO> APW19990516.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 19:51:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Inmate Paralyzed by Guard Paid $2M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The state has agreed to pay $2.2 million to  
an inmate paralyzed by a guard's bullet during a fight at Corcoran 
State Prison, the Los Angeles Times reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Department of Corrections admitted no wrongdoing in the  
settlement reached this month, according to the newspaper report. 
</P>
<P>
	Vincent Tulumis, 33, was shot in the neck during a May 1993  
fight allegedly set up by a guard, and neither fighting inmate was 
armed or posing a serious threat to the other when the shot was 
fired, according to depositions in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was clearly in the best interests of the state to see if a  
settlement could be made short of continued litigation,'' Cal 
Terhune, state corrections director, told the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Tulumis was serving a three-year sentence for drug possession  
and was nine months shy of his release at the time of the shooting. 
Paralyzed from the neck down, Tulimis said the settlement doesn't 
compensate all he's lost. 
</P>
<P>
	Tulumis said the fight was instigated by two guards, echoing  
claims by others inmates. From 1989 to 1995, seven inmates were 
killed and 43 were wounded by guards firing assault rifles to stop 
inmate fights at Corcoran, the paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the Corrections Department requested more than $91  
million in additional funds from the Legislature to cover a deficit 
partly due to unforeseen legal costs associated with brutality 
cases and inmate medical costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
