<DOCNO> APW19990516.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 16:31:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Search Ongoing for Fugitive Killers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTEZUMA CREEK, Utah (AP) -- Oliver Coho has never met Alan  
Lamont Pilon or Jason Wayne McVean, but he knows plenty about them. 
</P>
<P>
	For the better part of a year, the Navajo policeman has been  
tracking the two accused killers of a Cortez, Colo., officer 
through the canyons, creek beds and caves of southeastern Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	Coho knows Pilon wears military boots -- size 13 wide. He knows  
both men got new boots last year when they learned they were being 
tracked. He knows one smokes Marlboro Lights. And he knows McVean 
drinks too much. 
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't seen them, but we know they're still there,'' Coho  
says, his face sun-bronzed from his excursions into the wilderness. 
The clues tell him so. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Officer Dale Claxton was on routine patrol May 29, 1998, when he  
stumbled upon three men in a stolen water truck on a bridge 
southeast of Cortez. They opened fire with automatic weapons, 
hitting Claxton and his cruiser 26 times before he could even 
unbuckle his seatbelt. 
</P>
<P>
	In the ensuing chase and shootout, two Montezuma County  
sheriff's deputies were wounded. Suspect Robert Mason was found 
dead of a self-inflicted gunshot days later some 55 miles away near 
Bluff, Utah, after he wounded a San Juan County, Utah, deputy. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities had almost immediately identified the suspects in  
Claxton's killing as McVean, Pilon and Mason and learned all three 
were survivalists. The two surviving suspects eluded a huge search 
in early June through parts of Colorado and Utah. At the height of 
the nine-day search, more than 500 searchers from 51 agencies 
joined the effort, including the FBI, police and sheriff's deputies 
on horseback and in helicopters. 
</P>
<P>
	Searches of the men's homes turned up literature protesting  
tactics used by the Internal Revenue Service. Police Chief Roy Lane 
says Cortez, although hundreds of miles from the nearest seat of 
government, is a haven for anti-government groups -- ``people who 
don't like taxes, who won't put license plates on their cars, who 
don't believe in drivers' licenses. But we've never had any 
violence before,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	Police also found maps with circles, indicating caves along  
Montezuma Creek, places to hide out and stash food. Police learned 
the suspects had been going into the area for two or three years, 
with only enough food for a week. 
</P>
<P>
	``They aren't novices. They know what they're doing,'' Lane  
says. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The memorial on the bridge is simple. ``Officer Dale Claxton.  
Lobo 11 (his police call sign). May 29, 1998.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An evergreen planted nearby is hung with bows and a rosary. A  
white cross marks the spot. A toy bunny in a basket reminds people 
of the four children and widow he left behind. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, more than $40,000 has been raised to help Sue Claxton  
pay off her $86,000 mortgage, and she still drops by the police 
department. 
</P>
<P>
	``She knows we still consider her family,'' Lane says.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	More than 20 sightings of the two suspects have been reported  
over the year, and police have responded to each one. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, Coho shouldered his backpack -- loaded with fruit,  
sandwiches, plenty of water and his guns -- and walked 4 miles 
through the snow after yet another sighting. 
</P>
<P>
	Coho grew up in Ramah, N.M., and learned his tracking skills  
herding sheep. The rolling scrub, hills and washes where he lives 
in a trailer about 45 miles west of Cortez reminds him a lot of 
where he grew up. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's rugged and there are a lot of caves here,'' he says.  
</P>
<P>
	Coho also knows the area north of town where the two men are  
believed to have spent the winter. For five years, he has gone 
there for firewood. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen the places they walked. I've seen their  
footprints,'' he says. The fact that those footprints changed last 
October -- with a swap in the distinctive treads of the military 
boots Pilon wears -- tells him they're getting help from the 
outside. 
</P>
<P>
	He has found scattered cigarette butts and mounds of empty beer  
cans along river banks. Others in the Navajo nation have reported 
unfamiliar vehicles, and one man recently said he saw Pilon and 
McVean in a group of men drinking beer. 
</P>
<P>
	Coho knows he's getting close. Two months ago two men in a van,  
believed to be associates of the suspects, threatened a girl whose 
picture had appeared in the local newspaper after she reported 
seeing Pilon and McVean. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know they're here,'' Coho says softly.  
</P>
<P>
	Others aren't so sure. Some believe the pair died trying to  
hide. Others think they fled to hole up in Montana or Idaho with 
anti-government sympathizers. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	George Cuckie, 41, a construction worker who says he moved to  
Cortez to escape Denver's rat race, said there were a lot of 
antigovernment sympathizers around Cortez who could help the 
fugitives. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's inconceivable those two men could stay out that long  
without some outside help. A lot of the sightings are probably 
pranks to keep law enforcement officers off track,'' he suggests. 
</P>
<P>
	Lane is also convinced the two men are still in caves around  
Cortez and vows they will be captured eventually. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no doubt in my mind they're getting help,'' he says.  
``They can go without food for a while, but they had to get dry 
shoes. They had help to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lane sees parallels between McVean and Pilon and fugitive Eric  
Rudolph, accused in three bombings in Atlanta and one in 
Birmingham, Ala., but able to evade authorities in the rugged 
mountains of North Carolina for the last 16 months. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're going to see more people doing this to avoid  
arrest,'' Lane says. ``Rudolph has succeeded. McVean and Pilon have 
succeeded. There will be others who think they can elude the 
police. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll get them at some point. They're the ones living in the  
elements. It's easier for us to wait them out than for them to wait 
us out.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
