<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Portrait of Clockmaker Peter Burke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILLIPSBURG, N.J. (AP) -- Peter Burke kneels and offers a silent  
prayer before beginning another ascent. 
</P>
<P>
	Three wooden ladders take him from the serene, stained-glass  
interior of the 19th century church, up into the building's clock 
tower -- a place of chipping plaster, cooing pigeons and pungent 
machinery oil. 
</P>
<P>
	The clockmaker has spent countless hours in the tower over the  
last 4 1/2 years, working on the chimes and the timepiece with 6-foot 
faces. He dismantles pieces and hauls them home for repair, tinkers 
with motors and builds replacements for those that can't be fixed. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the biggest project he has ever undertaken. Except for an  
occasional payment for some machine parts, he is doing it gratis. 
And mostly in solitude. 
</P>
<P>
	Why? Burke, now 39, says it is a combination of his life's  
calling, a sinful past, a discovery of God. 
</P>
<P>
	A brass plate on the machine that runs the clock -- Burke calls  
it the ``brain'' -- says the clock was completed Nov. 5, 1910. It is 
Seth Thomas No. 1645, or the 45th in a series of its type. 
</P>
<P>
	The year 1910 marked the 50th anniversary of St. Philips and St.  
James' first Mass and the 25th for its edifice on South Main 
Street. The 109-foot spire, white above the red brick clock tower, 
was built to commemorate the occasions. 
</P>
<P>
	No one seems to remember when the clock stopped working. In the  
1960s, during the Delaware River community's centennial, a 
newspaper called the still-chiming timepiece one that ``watches 
over a town.'' Monsignor Michael Corona says residents in this 
former railroad town used to set their watches to the clock. 
</P>
<P>
	Clock tower legends abound. There's the man who plunged to his  
death while building the tower. And the pastor who didn't 
appreciate being awakened early by the chimes. Burke doesn't know 
what's true. He does say wires lifting the hammers that strike the 
1,000-pound bell appear to have been purposely destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	The clock was built with four faces so residents could tell time  
from any direction. Originally it was wound by hand. The motor came 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	It struck the hour and three times daily for the Angelus, a  
Catholic tradition traced to a 14th century pope who requested that 
bells be rung as an invitation to prayer. The Angelus strikes at 6 
a.m., noon and 6 p.m. -- three strokes, three times, with a pause 
after every third stroke, then nine strokes without a pause. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Angel of the Lord declared unto Mary ... '' Burke recites,  
then explains, ``It's the incarnation of Christ's invocation, 
incorporated into the clock. It represents the angel and our 
responsibility to the message that the angel brought.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's a prayer he knows by heart, and one he recites whether he's  
working on the clock or not. 
</P>
<P>
	Burke learned about the broken clock five years ago from his  
wife, who'd heard about it from a fellow parishioner. 
</P>
<P>
	Bats, pigeons, grease-clogged parts and water damage greeted  
Burke. An arm that helps move the dials had been repaired with a 
coffee can. And motor oil, not special clock oil, had been used to 
maintain it. 
</P>
<P>
	With the help of a contractor friend, Burke cleaned up the place  
and installed lighting, heating and pulleys to hoist parts and 
tools. Then came the task of figuring out what was wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of it's new to me. Eventually, I'll figure it out. I talk  
to other people in my trade. There's very few that do work on tower 
clocks,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like working on a watch, sitting on a bench. You have  
to be young and in good shape ... and willing to get dirty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the early 1980s, Burke attended a clock-making school in New  
York and apprenticed with a watchmaker at a jewelry store. After a 
stint at another jewelry store, he landed a job with Tag Heuer at 
the Swiss company's U.S. headquarters in Springfield. He has worked 
there, the world's third largest watch company, for nearly a 
decade. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one of Burke's three weeks of paid vacation is devoted  
to working on the clock, as are some weekends and holidays. 
Donations have enabled the church to pay a few thousand dollars for 
parts and machinery, but most of the work is labor-intensive. 
</P>
<P>
	Burke dismantled pieces, cut the grease in cleaning tanks at a  
shop in his home and rebuilt and repainted. 
</P>
<P>
	The clockwork is nearly complete. The chimes are next. He has no  
firm deadline but hopes it will chime in time for the millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll just thank God that He allows me to finish this,'' he  
says, stroking a piece made to look like a cross. ``I figured 
that's who this is for: God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burke has leaned heavily on the church throughout his life. He  
admits ``a lot of sin and misunderstanding,'' but declines to 
elaborate. He joined the parish of when he moved here 11 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	But he says he ``hooked into the church'' more recently --  
actually around the same time he learned of the broken clock. With 
a teacher at his daughter's Catholic school, Burke started reading 
and discussing religious scriptures and parables. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was getting deeper into prayer,'' he remembers. ``Finally, I  
went to confession five years ago, and I just needed to go over my 
whole life. It was like a great weight lifted off from me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He considers his ability to repair clocks a gift from God that  
now he can give back. ``I make that my prayer, my work, so I want 
to do the best work I can do,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just want someone to walk down the street and say, `Oh look,  
the clock's working.' They don't need to know who did it or how it 
happened.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
