<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tim Hardaway Fizzles in Game Five </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- When Tim Hardaway's last-second shot swished to end  
the first half, he jumped for joy and punched the air with his 
fist. 
</P>
<P>
	That was Hardaway's last basket, and his last celebration.  
</P>
<P>
	The Miami Heat's struggling star went scoreless in the second  
half, a goose egg that loomed large in the New York Knicks' 78-77 
victory Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway's series-long shooting slump appeared to be in the past  
when he made his first two attempts. He had nine points at 
halftime, including the buzzer-beater from 22 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hardaway took just two shots in the second half and missed  
them both. Worse, his turnover with 20 seconds left gave the Knicks 
the ball, and they took advantage when Allan Houston hit the 
game-winner with 0.8 seconds left to win the series 3-2. 
</P>
<P>
	``I put a lot on my shoulders,'' Hardaway said. ``I wasn't able  
to produce the whole series, and I turned it over in the last 30 
seconds and cost us the ballgame.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway went 4-for-10 to end the series 15-for-56 (27 percent).  
He went 0-for-3 from 3-point range to finish 5-for-25 (20 percent). 
</P>
<P>
	Teammates defended Hardaway's lack of offense.  
</P>
<P>
	``Timmy is not at fault,'' Alonzo Mourning said. ``Collectively  
we made mistakes. Anyone who blames Tim is full of bull.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But in such a close series, it's clear the Heat needed Hardaway  
at his best. He averaged 17.4 points per game this season and 
barely half that -- 9.0 -- in the series. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, Hardaway scored 38 points to lead the Heat to a  
Game 7 victory over New York. There were no such heroics in this 
year's winner-take-all showdown. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the lowest,'' Hardaway said. ``It hurts.''  
</P>
<P>
	A collision in February with Grant Hill left Hardaway with a  
bruise and hyperextension below his right knee. Before the series 
he complained that the injury still bothers him; more recently he 
refused to discuss it. 
</P>
<P>
	At any rate, the 32-year-old Hardaway looked older than his age  
for most of the series. And without his shot, the Heat simply 
didn't have enough scoring punch. 
</P>
<P>
	Terry Porter, Voshon Lenard and Clarence Weatherspoon -- who  
played pivotal roles in Miami's Game 4 win -- shot a combined 
3-for-15 Sunday and totaled just 12 points. Starting guard Dan 
Majerle had three points and scored 20 in the series. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway, meanwhile, never got hot.  
</P>
<P>
	``The shots I took, I missed,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	He was speaking of the second half, but he could have been  
talking about the entire series. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
