<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wolves Took Step Backward in '99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Flip Saunders insists the Minnesota  
Timberwolves will fill their two most pressing needs this summer, 
getting a center who can play the low post and a guard who can 
create problems by getting to the basket. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guarantee that this offseason will be a big offseason for  
us,'' the coach said. ``And we will do a lot of things to put a 
spark back in our organization like where it was last year at this 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, they could have solved their problems in January had  
Kevin McHale, Minnesota's vice president of basketball operations, 
accepted the Los Angeles' Lakers offer of Eddie Jones and Elden 
Campbell for Tom Gugliotta. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Gugliotta left Minnesota for Phoenix and a six-year  
contract worth about $60 million, some $27 million less than he 
could have had in Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Had McHale agreed to that deal, maybe Stephon Marbury wouldn't  
have forced his trade to New Jersey, leaving the Wolves with point 
guard Terrell Brandon, who will play the free-agent field. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was not the season we had wanted, being an eighth seed  
and being knocked out in the first round,'' center Dean Garrett 
said. ``We had trades, injuries and new guys coming all year. We 
can't afford to have guys coming in late to our system. We need to 
have everyone here all season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The departures of Gugliotta and Marbury left the Wolves with  
just one star, Kevin Garnett, who couldn't carry the team by 
himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were just starting to create a rhythm,'' Garnett said. ``I  
was getting a feel for others' games. I had dreams of us going far 
in the playoffs. I don't know what to expect now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Garnett said reaching the playoffs, even at 25-25, took a  
little of the sting away. 
</P>
<P>
	``With what we have been through and who we have lost, people  
didn't expect us to get this far,'' he said. ``Some of our guys 
didn't know what the playoffs were about. They learned that 
defending at home is important. At least people could take some 
good things out of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This was a season full of what-ifs for the Wolves, who were  
bounced from the playoffs in the first round for the third straight 
season, this time 3-1 by the top-seeded San Antonio Spurs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're disappointed,'' Brandon said. ``You could say if we had  
more time to jell, we could have done better. But we were still 
able to make the playoffs. We played as hard as we could. If the 
young players continue to listen to and learn from the veteran 
players, the sky's the limit for this franchise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Wolves had the Nets' lottery pick and their own, No. 14, in  
the draft next month, and they'll try to be a player in the free 
agent market, too. 
</P>
<P>
	The one thing Saunders wants to scrap is his team's reliance on  
the jump shot. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to get a player, one way or another, whether it's a  
perimeter player or an inside player, that can get to the basket 
and get fouled,'' Saunders said. ``I bet over the last three or 
four weeks of the season we probably outscored everybody we played 
from the field but we've been beat up at the free throw line. 
</P>
<P>
	``In order to take the next step, we've got to be able to go at  
David Robinson, go at Tim Duncan, get them in some foul trouble and 
get ourselves to the free throw line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Smith, who signed a paltry $1.75 million one-year contract  
for the chance to reestablish himself as one of the league's 
bright, young stars, might sign a long-term extension with the 
Wolves. 
</P>
<P>
	Brandon is another story.  
</P>
<P>
	He wants to know what it feels like to be courted by some  
big-bucks owner and even though his agent, Bill Duffy, is a former 
college roommate of McHale's, keeping him from bolting to sunnier 
climes is going to be difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just once I want to know what it feels like to be a free  
agent,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	And just once the Wolves would like to know what it feels like  
to reach Round 2 in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our No. 1 focus, we need to bring in a dynamic player,''  
Saunders said. ``To add energy to our team. And I think we owe it 
to our fans, also, to show our commitment. We need to get long-term 
commitments from our players so our fans know we're going to be a 
team that's going to be here and a team that you can build and keep 
it together and have a chance to win championships.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One bright spot in the Wolves' future is 7-foot rookie center  
Radoslav Nesterovic of Slovenia, who signed just before the 
playoffs and held his own against David Robinson in 18 minutes of 
playing time Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Garnett, who was disappointed at being snubbed for the NBA's  
all-defensive team, said he welcomed the break, albeit earlier than 
he wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to sleep until 5 in the afternoon. I'm going to  
visit my mom and grandma. I'm going to see some Lynx games and 
cheer them on,'' he said. ``I want to live it up. 
</P>
<P>
	``But at the same time, I'm going to be back in the lab to see  
what I can do better,'' Garnett said. ``Hopefully, next year, I'll 
make first-team something. I want to be the best.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
