<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sacramento Laments Missed Chances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- While the Sacramento Kings took the Utah  
Jazz to the brink of elimination, their failure to push the Jazz 
over the brink -- either in Game 4 or Game 5 -- left them frustrated. 
</P>
<P>
	``I honestly thought we outplayed them in the series,'' said Jon  
Barry, who scored 14 points in the Kings' 99-92 overtime loss in 
Game 5 while playing 38 minutes. ``We just didn't come out on top. 
I feel like we won today's game. We proved we have tremendous 
heart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last two games of the series -- Game 4, which was won on a  
last-gasp jumper by John Stockton, and the overtime nail-biter in 
Game 5 -- made elimination particularly hard to take for Chris 
Webber. 
</P>
<P>
	``That hurts,'' said Webber, who scored 12 points and grabbed 14  
rebounds Sunday but had just three points after halftime and was 
5-for-17 from the field. ``We really felt like we would win today 
and win the series. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't feel I played my best series, especially today. But we  
wanted to make them (Jazz) look old, and we started to make them 
look old. We saw them at their weakest and we saw them at their 
strongest. We wanted to be the ones to upset them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Kings looked as if they were going to do just that. Vlade  
Divac made a hook shot in the lane over Karl Malone with 58 seconds 
to play to give the Kings an 88-85 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	After Bryon Russell made a 3-pointer from the right corner to  
tie it with 48.5 seconds to play, Sacramento and Divac had two more 
good chances. But Divac missed a layup with 30 seconds to play, and 
after he rebounded a miss by John Stockton with 9.2 seconds left, 
the Kings set up their final play for Divac. 
</P>
<P>
	His hook shot slid off the rim as time expired. In overtime, the  
Jazz ended the Kings' Cinderella story. 
</P>
<P>
	``Vlade had a good look,'' said coach Rick Adelman, his eyes  
welling with tears. ``We just didn't get it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Webber: ``We had confidence in Vlade. We thought we were  
going to win on that shot. You can't get a better chance than Vlade 
and the 'Kareem' hook.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Kings' youth showed in the game, as Sacramento was 6-for-29  
on 3-pointers and a meager 18-of-30 on the free throw line. Rookie 
point guard Jason Williams was 1-for-6 from the field and missed 
all three of his 3-pointers. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry and Vernon Maxwell had huge games off the bench for  
Sacramento. Barry scored 14 points, while Maxwell had 22 points in 
place of Williams and kept the Kings in the game in the second 
half. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite being eliminated in the first round, the Kings players  
said they proved something to the league. 
</P>
<P>
	``We came in here, and they thought it was going to be an easy  
win,'' Maxwell said. ``We took them to overtime. We feel good about 
ourselves, because we weren't even supposed to be in this 
predicament. ... We still feel strong and feel good about 
ourselves. We're looking forward to next year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Before the season, we weren't even thinking about the  
playoffs,'' said Divac. ``We got in and almost won. But you can't 
be satisfied. You always want to try to get more, and try to 
improve.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
