<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Magic Season Ends in Disappointment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- The end had a familiar feel for the Orlando  
Magic, who spent much of the season overachieving only to lose in 
the opening round of the NBA playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Penny Hardaway's offense was nowhere to be found when the team  
needed him most, letting down a club that heightened expectations 
by sharing the best record in the Eastern Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen Iverson led the Philadelphia 76ers to a 3-1 victory in  
their best-of-5 series with Orlando in part because he outplayed 
the Magic's leading scorer. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway averaged 19 in the series. However, he struggled to get  
involved offensively in the last three games and enjoyed most of 
his success after the Magic trailed by double digits in Games 3 and 
4. 
</P>
<P>
	He complained after the third game that coach Chuck Daly wasn't  
running enough plays for him, then missed his first nine shots on 
the way to a 3-for-17 performance in Saturday's 91-81 loss that 
ended the season. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the questions the Magic and their star have to resolve  
during the offseason is whether Hardaway, once billed as the next 
Michael Jordan, has played his last game for Orlando. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-time All-Star has said he plans to exercise an option  
in his contract that allows him to become a free agent. And 
although he's also said he'd like to remain with the Magic, the 
team could elect to re-sign and trade him. 
</P>
<P>
	Daly, finishing the second-year of his contract, also has a  
decision to make. He has an option to return as coach at $5 
million, take a $200,000 consultant job with the Magic or move to 
another team. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're hoping that both Chuck and Penny are back,'' said  
general manager John Gabriel. ``I think in this series, we learned 
some things about this team. We'll evaluate and see where we need 
to add to take the next step.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Daly called the season perhaps his most enjoyable in coaching.  
The Magic began the lockout-shortened schedule thinking they'd earn 
the seventh or eighth playoff seed and wound up winning 33 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Players bought Daly's concept that good defense not only would  
shut down opponents, but create more opportunities on offense than 
a playbook ever could. 
</P>
<P>
	Rookies Matt Harpring and Michael Doleac proved to be quick  
learners and contributed despite not having the benefit of a 
regular training camp to prepare for their first season. 
</P>
<P>
	And despite a strained relationship, Daly and Hardaway got along  
well enough that the Magic overachieved until a season-high, 
five-game losing streak threatened to tear the team apart. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway, who had struggled at point guard, and Nick Anderson  
bickered over which of them should play off-guard. They were urged 
to stop feuding during a players-only meeting, and the team 
responded by winning the last four games going into the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	With or without Hardaway, finding help at point guard will be a  
priority. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Darrell Armstrong had his best season, earning the  
NBA's Sixth Man award, Hardaway's desire to play shooting guard 
makes it essential to add another playmaker. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel pretty good about what this group was able to  
accomplish,'' Daly said. ``We're not where we want to be, not as 
good as we can be, but we've made a lot of improvement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The stage was set for an early playoff exit when the Magic lost  
Game 1 in Orlando, dropping homecourt advantage. They held Iverson 
to 13 points to win Game 2, but the league scoring champion and his 
energetic young teammates were too much to overcome on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was an awkward year with the lockout and then playing so  
many games in so short of a time. But we overachieved all season 
long. We really played over our heads ... Nobody expected us to get 
33 wins and become a favorite,'' Hardaway said. 
</P>
<P>
	``But then we get into the playoffs and get a draw like  
Philadelphia, who has played us tough all year long. They've sort 
of had our number. But this season was not a failure.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
