<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Italy Floats Cease-Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Italy's premier has proposed that NATO call a  
cease-fire in its air campaign against Yugoslavia if Russia and 
China approve a U.N. Security Council resolution outlining the 
allies' peace terms, according to an interview published Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	However, should Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic reject the  
resolution, NATO would step up the attack with ground troops, La 
Repubblica daily quoted Massimo D'Alema as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	D'Alema, whose country is a key base for the air campaign  
against Yugoslavia, said he had raised his proposal with France and 
with NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana, and would bring it up 
with Germany's leader this week, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian premier has faced opposition to the NATO campaign by  
the public and opposition parties, and by some members of his 
center-left coalition. Anti-war activists marched Sunday demanding 
a NATO cease-fire. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO has rejected calls for a halt in the bombing campaign until  
Milosevic accepts its demands. 
</P>
<P>
	However, in Brussels, Belgium, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said  
the alliance ``welcomes all diplomatic initiatives that can help to 
resolve this crisis on the basis of the five conditions of the 
international community, without which the crisis cannot be 
resolved, but only postponed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The plan approved by Russia and Western allies earlier this  
month demands Yugoslavia accept an international force in Kosovo 
and the return of ethnic Albanian refugees. Diplomats are working 
to push through a Security Council resolution upholding the terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia and China, which oppose the NATO campaign, have called  
for it to be halted to allow for peace efforts. D'Alema's proposed 
cease-fire presumably would entice their support for the resolution 
and give Milosevic breathing room to accept. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that the United Nations' entry into the field with a  
political initiative would offer a way out for Serb pride,'' he was 
quoted by La Repubblica as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	If it doesn't, he said, ``we would need to send ground troops.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
