<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Czechs Win World Hockey Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LILLEHAMMER, Norway (AP) -- Jan Hlavac beat Finnish goalie Miikka  
Kiprusoff off a rebound at 16:32 of overtime Sunday, giving the 
Czech Republic its seventh World Hockey Championships title. 
</P>
<P>
	Finland, last year's losing finalist to Sweden, won Sunday's  
second final game 4-1 to force the 20-minute overtime. The Czech 
Republic won the opener 3-1 Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Czechs carried the play in overtime and had several scoring  
chances before Hlavac's winner. The Finns, supported by thousands 
of fans in Olympic Hakons Hall, failed to generate any offense in 
the extra period. 
</P>
<P>
	Goalie Milan Hnilicka, the hero Saturday, had a nightmarish  
start, surrendering two goals less than six minutes into the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Defenseman Antti-Jussi Niemo fired a slap shot past Hnilicka  
from the right circle at 1:41, and Juha Lind, who scored the Finns' 
one goal Saturday, made it 2-0 at 5:35. 
</P>
<P>
	Marko Tuomainen tipped in Jere Karalahti's slap shot from the  
blue line, giving the Finns a 3-0 lead at 1:51 of the second period 
with the Czechs shorthanded. 
</P>
<P>
	Viktor Ujcik broke away to score for the Czechs at 10:47, with  
the puck taking a lucky bounce off Kiprusoff's pads and hitting the 
post before trickling over the goal line. 
</P>
<P>
	Ville Peltonen, who was his team's top scorer when Finland won  
its only previous world championship over Sweden in 1995, connected 
with another slap shot from the left circle early in the third 
period for Finland's fourth goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Saku Koivu, the Montreal Canadiens star who led tournament  
scorers with four goals and 12 assists, missed the second final 
because of an arm injury. The Finnish captain was slashed late in 
the third period Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweden beat Canada in Saturday's bronze-medal game.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
