<DOCNO> APW19990516.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 15:51:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Fund-Raising Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) -- President Clinton slipped his right  
hand into his pants pocket and his voice eased into a 
conversational tone: ``Let's talk about the entertainment issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The eyes on him, from a small stone patio overlooking the lights  
of Los Angeles, belonged to Hollywood's hottest -- Jeffrey 
Katzenberg, David Geffen, Rob Reiner, Goldie Hawn, Kurt Russell, 
Dennis Quaid and Steven Spielberg, whom Clinton called ``Steve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All had just paid the Democratic Party between $25,000 and  
$100,000 for a Wolfgang Puck-catered dinner with the president. 
``You've helped me through thick and thin for all these long 
years,'' Clinton told the intimate assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	So it was that Clinton, pushing a national campaign against the  
kind of youth violence seen in the Colorado school shootings, only 
gently took entertainment types to task for movies and TV shows 
that glorify violence. He softly prodded changes in their ads and 
ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no call for finger-pointing here. ... We are  
determined to do this as a family,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He spoke Saturday at Greystone Mansion, a city-owned landmark  
that was the set of ``Ghostbusters II,'' in which only the 
paranormal were liquefied to green goo by phaser-like guns. 
</P>
<P>
	Hawn, squeezing past reporters to sneak a smoke with Kurt  
Russell, ignored questions about the president's challenge to 
Hollywood. Lisa Kudrow, of TV's ``Friends,'' played dumb: ``What? I 
haven't spoken to him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, before leaving Los Angeles for San Diego, Clinton  
stopped for brunch at the Malibu home of Barbara Streisand and her 
husband James Brolin. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Welcome gun manufacturers to that family Clinton spoke about.  
</P>
<P>
	In a series of fund-raising speeches on this $3-million West  
Coast weekend swing for Democrats, Clinton has been singing praise 
for the gun makers' support of crackdowns on gun show sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitting them against the National Rifle Association, Clinton  
said he was ``very proud'' of gun makers ``who for years sided 
always with the NRA ... and who supported the legislation this time 
in Congress and had the kind of civic responsibility that we need 
more from every American.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	They say Clinton has a steel-trap memory.  
</P>
<P>
	Exhibit A: Friday night's speech to donors in Portola Valley,  
Calif., where Clinton recalled in vivid detail a Tina Turner 
concert in Little Rock, Ark., more than a decade ago. He and five 
friends in the middle of the front row. 
</P>
<P>
	``I forget, Hillary had to go some place that night. ...  
</P>
<P>
	``And behind us there was a lady I later found out was a  
hairdresser in a small town about 50 miles away, dressed in a tiger 
outfit complete with ears and tail and everything. It was an 
interesting night, all right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Exhibit B: Saturday's $2 million dinner with the stars. ``I was  
laughing with Goldie Hawn tonight because I remember her being in 
the Biltmore in Los Angeles on June 2, 1992, when I was nominated 
for president ... all the stories were the exit polls showing that 
Ross Perot was really in first place.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Dinner with the president: $25,000 to $100,000 per couple. Shoes  
optional. 
</P>
<P>
	Hawn padded around the elegant and Gothic-styled Greystone  
Mansion in halter top and bare feet, picking at her rat's nest 
hairdo. Spielberg and Geffen wore white sneakers. Russell sported 
cowboy boots. Quaid was in T-shirts, jeans and bomber jacket. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was one of the few who bothered with a necktie.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The president spoke in Beverly Hills after a free day with his  
daughter, Chelsea, at the secluded, northern California hillside 
home of computer magnate Steven Jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Neighbors said father and daughter took a walk together. Clinton  
said Hillary Rodham Clinton joined in the day by telephone. ``We 
called her and then we got lonesome and we'd call her again,'' he 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton painted a portrait of cozy domesticity remembering the  
family's pre-White House life in the Arkansas governor's mansion. 
``I was happy as a clam at home, with Hillary and Chelsea and the 
life we had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Looking ahead, Clinton said he was consulting on his Little  
Rock, Ark., presidential library with Spielberg. ``We were talking 
about whether we could have some virtual reality effects in my 
library in the museum, you know,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes I feel like I'm living in virtual reality, so I'm  
highly interested in this.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Wrapping up his fund-raising sprint from Seattle to the San  
Francisco Bay area to Beverly Hills, to San Diego to Las Vegas, 
Clinton decided Sunday to skip a scheduled ``down'' day on the golf 
courses of Vegas and return to Washington Monday seven hours 
earlier than originally planned. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides said the president looked ahead to an over-full travel  
schedule for the week -- New York on Wednesday, Littleton, Colo., on 
Thursday, Virginia on Saturday, and Grambling, La., on Sunday -- and 
decided he needed some more time in the office on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990516.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 15:11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  US Women Beat the Dutch in Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Mia Hamm tied the career record for international  
goals Sunday and helped send the U.S. women's soccer team past the 
Netherlands 3-0, its second victory over the Dutch in three days. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamm, the country's most popular female soccer player, scored  
her 107th goal in the 53rd minute in this tuneup game for next 
month's Women's World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	She took cross from Cindy Parlow and dribbled between two  
defenders before scoring with her left foot. The shot hit the 
crossbar and dropped for the goal and a 2-0 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamm, playing her 171st game with the national team, shares the  
goals record with Italy's Elisabetta Vignotto, who played in the 
1970s and 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd roared as the ball hit the ground, and Hamm raised her  
right arm. She jumped and pumped her fist before being surrounded 
by her teammates. The ball was retrieved for her and marked with 
No. 107. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamm also assisted on Brandi Chastain's second goal, a header in  
the 81st minute. Hamm had a chance to set the record in the 54th 
and 59th minutes, but both shots went wide. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States is 12-2-1 this year, including 6-1 on the tour  
leading to the World Cup. The U.S. women will play two more games 
before the showcase event, which begins June 19. The U.S. roster 
for the World Cup will be announced Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States, which has lost just once at home in the last  
55 matches, was on the Dutch side of the field for almost the 
entire game. The Americans outshot the Netherlands 26-2. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States got the only goal it needed in the 14th  
minute. There was a battle for the ball in front of the Dutch goal 
before Chastain got control and shot sharply into the upper right 
corner of the net. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States has outscored its opponents 23-0 in the last  
four games, including a 5-0 victory over the Dutch on Thursday in 
Milwaukee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990516.0107 </DOCNO>
