<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blackhawks Jump to No. 4 in Lottery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Chicago Blackhawks cashed in on a longshot  
Sunday, converting a 3.7 percent chance to improve their spot in 
the NHL draft and moving up the maximum four spots from No. 8 to 
No. 4. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tampa Bay Lightning retained the No. 1 overall selection,  
with the No. 2 spot going to the expansion Atlanta Thrashers. 
</P>
<P>
	Only the four teams with the fewest regular season points --  
Tampa Bay, New York Islanders, Vancouver and Nashville -- and 
Atlanta had a chance at the No. 1 pick, and no team could move up 
more than four places. 
</P>
<P>
	Tampa Bay, with 47 points, had a 26 percent chance of getting  
the No. 1 pick and was able to retain the selection based on 
numerical combinations produced by a lottery machine. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be the second straight year that the Lightning get the  
No. 1 choice. They acquired the pick in two trades last year, 
moving up from No. 3 to select center Vincent Lecavalier, who had 
13 goals and 15 assists in 82 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Vancouver picks third, and after Chicago, the order of the draft  
will be the Islanders, Nashville, Washington, Los Angeles, Calgary, 
Montreal, the New York Rangers, Florida, Edmonton and San Jose. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, Anaheim. Carolina, St. Louis, Pittsburgh, Phoenix,  
Buffalo, Boston, Philadelphia, Chicago (acquired from Detroit), 
Toronto, Colorado, Ottawa, New Jersey and Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the Pavel Bure trade, Florida has the option to give  
Vancouver its No. 1 pick this year or next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blackhawks had the eighth-best chance of having their number  
sequence selected in the drawing, a weighted system that afforded 
teams with the fewest points the best chance of moving up. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be the first time since 1984 that the Blackhawks pick  
fourth or higher. They chose Ed Olczyk third overall that year. 
</P>
<P>
	The entry draft is set for Saturday, June 26, at the FleetCenter  
in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Center Patrik Stefan of the IHL's Long Beach Ice Dogs is the  
top-rated skater in North America in the final rankings compiled by 
the NHL's Central Scouting Service. The Czech Republic native had 
11 goals and 24 assists in 33 games but sustained a season-ending 
concussion March 31 after missing three months with another 
concussion and a spinal contusion earlier in the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Pavel Brendl, a right-wing for the WHL's Calgary Hitmen, is the  
No. 2 rated player. He finished the season as the league's top 
scorer with 73 goals and 61 assists in 68 games, and was the WHL 
Rookie of the Year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
