<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forbes: 14 Baseball Teams in Red </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Fourteen of the 30 major league baseball teams  
posted operating losses last year, Forbes magazine reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles Dodgers lost $11.7 million on an estimated $108  
million in revenue -- in large part because of baseball's 
revenue-sharing system, which has baseball's top 13 
revenue-generating teams contributing $100 million to the 15 teams 
with the lowest revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	That didn't stop the New York Yankees -- which had to pay $13  
million in revenue sharing -- from raking in $23 million in net 
income on a league-best $175.5 million in 1998 revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not surprising, then, that Forbes estimates the New York  
Yankees' value at $491 million, the best in baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cleveland Indians, put up for sale last week by owner Dick  
Jacobs, carry the second-highest value at $359 million, according 
to the Forbes survey. 
</P>
<P>
	The estimated values, based on a formula taking into account  
team revenues, the stadium, debt and city demographics, do not 
necessarily reflect what a team could get on the open market. 
</P>
<P>
	When he announced that he was selling the team, Jacobs spoke of  
getting $800 million, the amount offered for the NFL's Washington 
Redskins. 
</P>
<P>
	The last baseball team sold was the Los Angeles Dodgers, with  
Rupert Murdoch paying $350 million in 1998 for the franchise, 
Dodgers Stadium, the spring training complex in Vero Beach, Fla., 
and property in the Dominican Republic. Forbes values the Dodgers 
at $270 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Other teams recording operating losses included the Kansas City  
Royals ($10.9 million), Toronto Blue Jays ($9.5 million), Milwaukee 
Brewers ($8.8 million), Seattle Mariners ($8.6 million) San Diego 
Padres ($8 million), Chicago Cubs ($7.9 million) and Boston Red Sox 
($7.6 million). 
</P>
<P>
	Also in the red were the Minnesota Twins ($7.1 million), San  
Francisco Giants ($6.4 million), New York Mets ($5.2 million), 
Detroit Tigers ($4.5 million), Houston Astros ($3.7 million) and 
Anaheim Angels ($200,000). 
</P>
<P>
	After the Yankees, the next five highest operating incomes were  
Arizona ($22.5 million), Tampa Bay ($20.6 million), Colorado ($19.5 
million) Cleveland ($19 million) and Atlanta ($16.4 million). 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes defines operating income as revenues less player costs,  
selling, general and marketing expenses, stadium operations, 
coaches and player development costs and travel. It does not 
include earnings before interest, taxes and depreciation, though it 
does include revenue-sharing figures. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue-sharing income of $13 million allowed Montreal to record  
net income of $5.6 million, even though, according to Forbes, the 
Expos are the least valuable franchise at $84 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida Marlins, who slashed their payroll after winning the  
World Series in 1997, had $8.6 million in net income last year, 
thanks in part to $4 million from revenue sharing. 
</P>
<P>
 *For release 6:30 p.m. EDT -- time set by source    	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
