<HEADLINE> Martin Lovin' 'La Vida Loca' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Riding the frenzy over his hit song ``Livin' la  
Vida Loca,'' Ricky Martin is loving his crazy life. 
</P>
<P>
	``What, are you kidding me?'' Martin says in the May 24 issue of  
Time. ``I'm flying. I'm flying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The enthusiastic crowd gathered to see the Puerto Rican singing  
star at a Manhattan record store last week outnumbered the throng 
across the street lined up for an advance screening of the new 
``Star Wars'' movie. 
</P>
<P>
	His self-titled debut album in English follows a string of  
successful Spanish-language albums, which in turn followed his run 
in the youth group Menudo. The 27-year-old also has co-starred on 
Broadway in ``Les Miserables'' and has appeared on the soap opera 
``General Hospital.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the instant success of his new album, Martin still gets  
the same question: Why cross over? 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people say, `Well, why English, why do you want to do  
it in the States?''' Martin said. ``It's all about communication. 
The last album (`Vuelve') did really good, to be quite honest -- I 
want to be humble about this -- all over the world. One of the songs 
was No. 1 in 22 countries. And it was in Spanish. So I didn't have 
to go to English to make it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
