<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 05:21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lunch Deduction Bill Gains Ground </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Five years ago, Congress and President Clinton  
sharply curtailed a tax break for businesses by slashing the amount 
of business meals they could deduct. Restaurants took a hit, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``People do not use their business meal deduction as much,''  
said Perry Moy, owner of the Plum Garden Restaurant in McHenry, 
Ill. ``I lost 30 percent of my lunch business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers now are lining up behind legislation that gradually  
would restore the deduction, but only for smaller businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not for the fat cats. This is really for business  
people out there hustling business,'' said a lead sponsor, Rep. Jim 
McCrery, R-La. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, the deduction was cut from 80 percent to 50 percent of  
a meal's cost to help reduce the federal budget deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	Legislation sponsored by McCrery and Rep. John Tanner, D-Tenn.,  
would bring the deduction back to 80 percent over a six-year period 
beginning in 2000 -- but only for businesses with $5 million or less 
in annual gross receipts. 
</P>
<P>
	McCrery wants to help businesses struggling against big  
corporations and to defuse the argument that the measure would 
benefit wealthy business people and lobbyists who enjoy 
three-martini lunches. 
</P>
<P>
	Abe Schneier, lobbyist with the National Association of  
Wholesale Representatives, said meals often are the best times for 
a small-scale salesman or traveling representative to meet with 
clients and make deals. 
</P>
<P>
	``For them, the restaurant is their office,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	But sponsors say since the deduction was cut, the number of  
business meal spenders has dropped by more than 2 million, 
primarily among the self-employed and small businesses having a 
harder time absorbing the costs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the group least able to sustain an attack on their  
margins,'' McCrery said. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Restaurant Association is leading the lobbying  
charge for the measure. The group recently set up a lunch with 
local business people in Houston for the chairman of the House Ways 
and Means Committee, Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas. Placemats for the 
meal sported a favorable editorial from Archer's hometown Houston 
Chronicle. 
</P>
<P>
	``He acknowledged that he understands this isn't just a  
restaurant issue,'' said Kathleen O'Leary, a restaurant association 
lobbyist in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Archer would say only that Archer, whose  
committee has jurisdiction over taxes, has talked extensively with 
those interested in the measure but had made no commitment to 
support it. 
</P>
<P>
	Working in the sponsors' favor is the bill's relatively modest  
cost of about $3 billion over five years. In addition, Republican 
leaders are considering the measure as one way to offset costs on 
small business of a likely increase in the minimum wage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it (the minimum wage) would happen by itself,''  
said Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla. ``We have to find sweeteners for 
business so they don't go ballistic on us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although the proposal has significant Democratic support on  
Capitol Hill, the White House has not taken a public stand. 
</P>
<P>
	Initial drafts of this year's tax relief legislation will emerge  
in the House and Senate in July. Democrats and Republicans say the 
bill is most likely to include a variety of targeted tax breaks 
that are phased in slowly as anticipated non-Social Security budget 
surpluses grow. 
</P>
<P>
	The meal tax deduction would grow from 50 percent to 80 percent  
in 5 percent increments over six years, delaying its full cost 
impact -- and sponsors hope increasing its chances of passage. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can fashion the tax changes to take effect when we have the  
money,'' McCrery said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
