<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Jets Strike Serbs Hard  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO jets struck hard in Kosovo  
Sunday and early Monday, while NATO officials say they've grown 
increasingly suspicious that the Serbs used Kosovar civilians as 
human shields in a bombing that reportedly killed 87 people. 
Yugoslavia protested that the intensive bombing is obstructing a 
partial withdrawal of its troops from Kosovo -- a complaint NATO 
spokesman Jamie Shea dismissed. Meanwhile, a 15-member U.N. team 
arrived in Belgrade en route to Kosovo, where they'll get a 
first-hand look at the war-torn province. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. May Free Serb POWs  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two Serb POWs being held by the U.S. military  
in Germany are set to be released, possibly on Monday, a Pentagon 
official says, but there was no indication of any linkage between 
this release and that of three U.S. soldiers earlier this month. 
The pending release of the Serb soldiers comes after three U.S. 
Army soldiers captured along the Kosovo-Macedonia border were 
turned over earlier this month. The two Serbs were turned over to 
U.S. military authorities in Albania by the Kosovo Liberation Army. 

</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu, Barak Face Off  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel voters will choose a new leader Monday,  
with only two politicians on the ballot: incumbent Benjamin 
Netanyahu and Ehud Barak, a career military man likely to revive 
peacemaking efforts with the Palestinians. With the last two minor 
candidates dropping out Sunday, the contest was to be settled in a 
single ballot Monday. Netanyahu had hoped to push the race into a 
runoff, giving him two more weeks to campaign. Trailing in the 
polls, a combative Netanyahu nonetheless insisted that he'll win. 

</P>
<P>
	Two Killed in Iowa Twisters  
</P>
<P>
	LOGAN, Iowa (AP) -- Two people were killed as twisters rolled  
across western Iowa Sunday, authorities said. Another 14 people 
were injured. Names of those who died have not been released 
pending notification of relatives, said Jim Seymour, a hospital 
administrator. 

</P>
<P>
	New MBAs Flood Internet Businesses  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Fat paychecks, large bonuses, and a clear career  
track are being increasingly shunned by business school graduates 
who are taking a leap into the potential for phenomenal wealth and 
success offered by an Internet startup. The number of Harvard 
Business School graduates saying they plan to go into 
high-technology businesses or start their own businesses has been 
rising over the last few years, and the jump from 1998 to 1999 has 
been especially robust, according to an informal student poll of 
about 45 percent of this year's students. 

</P>
<P>
	New Prostate Treatment Unveiled  
</P>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A new procedure for reducing enlarged  
prostates is less painful then surgery and doesn't require an 
overnight hospital stay, the doctor who developed it says. Prostate 
enlargement, which is not related to cancer, requires surgery, 
medication or other treatment in one-fourth of men by age 80, and 
nearly all show signs of the disorder by 85. The procedure is done 
with a device that is threaded through the urethra to inject small 
amounts of purified alcohol into the prostate. The alcohol causes 
cells to take in too much water and die, thus shrinking the 
prostate. 

</P>
<P>
	IMF Ready To Work With Russia  
</P>
<P>
	LANGKAWI, Malaysia (AP) -- The International Monetary Fund said  
Sunday it was ready to work with Russia's new government but 
appealed to Moscow to enact new legislation to enable continued 
lending. It was the first IMF statement since Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin survived an impeachment vote yesterday. The political 
events in Russia created uncertainty that forced international 
financial institutions to review their programs to help Russia. The 
IMF has tentatively agreed to lend Russia $4.5 billion but is 
waiting for parliament to pass a legislative package on economic 
policy before disbursing the first installment. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Fall Sharply  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell sharply in early trading  
Monday. The Nikkei shed 268.73 points to 16,541.66 in early 
trading. On Friday, the average closed down 40.86 points. 

</P>
<P>
	Rockies Beat Diamondbacks  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Luis Gonzalez extended his hitting streak to 28  
games but his Arizona teammates could manage only six other hits 
against Pedro Astacio in the Diamondbacks' 5-1 loss to the Colorado 
Rockies on Sunday. Larry Walker hit a two-run single in a three-run 
third inning that extended his hitting streak to 17 games and 
Astacio (4-3) struck out four and had an RBI single in the eighth 
in his first complete game with Colorado. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
</TEXT>
