<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-16 09:41:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Star Wars' More About Storytelling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Marc Norman, the Academy Award-winning  
co-writer of ``Shakespeare in Love,'' recalls the day 22 years ago 
when his children went to see a new movie about battles in space. 
</P>
<P>
	``They dragged me back to the 2 o'clock show,'' Norman says.  
``It had gods, devils and Bible stories. I experienced what 
somebody might, in the face of a new religion -- I was scared.'' 
</P>
<P>
	People don't talk about ``Star Wars.'' They bow before it, in  
fear or in awe. Or they turn away, in disappointment or 
disinterest. Few refuse to acknowledge it. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1977, George Lucas did more than make history. ``Star Wars''  
went on to become the second-highest grossing movie of all time, 
behind only ``Titanic,'' and its two sequels would rank seventh and 
ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucas would also create a history, a modern mythology, populated  
by space adventurers called Luke and Han, a princess named Leia, 
the Wookiee co-pilot Chewbacca and droid sidekicks R2-D2 and C-3PO. 
His mythology influenced a generation in Hollywood and two 
generations of fans. It also became intertwined with his personal 
myth: reclusive filmmaker, Hollywood outsider, control freak. 
</P>
<P>
	The mythologies always threatened to swallow him, betray him,  
even today, as the world readies itself for a new religious 
experience with Wednesday's release of the prequel, ``Star Wars: 
Episode I -- The Phantom Menace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He urges restraint.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's only a movie. People should get a life,'' Lucas told a  
New York news conference this month. 
</P>
<P>
	``People should have a well-rounded life,'' he added. ``(The  
movies) are designed to make people think about the larger entities 
and the mysteries of life and hopefully raise questions. There 
definitely aren't enough answers in 'Star Wars' to constitute a 
religion. The point is to go and look through the religions and 
find something that has some answers for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Good and bad. Light and dark. A hero embarks on a journey of  
self-discovery. It doesn't get much more basic than that. Lucas's 
original ``Star Wars'' movie drew its Force from age-old tales. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing he's very good at, and I completely believe it's  
instinctual to him and not designed, is his ability to just lock 
onto the basic themes that people enjoy,'' says Dale Pollock, who 
wrote ``Skywalking: The Life and Films of George Lucas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pollock writes in a new chapter, added for an edition timed for  
release with ``The Phantom Menace,'' that while Lucas has 
``reinvented the entire process of movie making'' with computer 
technology, ``the point is not the technology, but the 
storytelling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, the technology didn't hurt. People of one generation  
remember where they were and what they were feeling the day 
President Kennedy was shot. People of another remember that first 
time they saw the space ship glide across the screen in the 
beginning of ``Star Wars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added to this was the soaring score by John Williams, music that  
``was definitely the turning point in my life,'' says ``Matrix'' 
composer, Don Davis, who recalls seeing the original ``Star Wars'' 
for this first time when he was studying music at UCLA. ``It gave 
everyone something to strive before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Movies just never looked like that before, never sounded like  
that before, never transported people to another time and place so 
completely. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think of the look of it, the feel of it, the emotion of it.  
You really got caught up in it,'' producer-screenwriter Dean Devlin 
says. ``I remember, I was 13 years old, at the Chinese Theater, 
opening day, and the whole audience started hissing when Darth 
Vader came on. I had never hissed a character in a movie in my 
life. But you knew this is the baddest guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Devlin, who himself grew up to create special effects-filled  
``popcorn movies'' like ``Godzilla'' and ``Independence Day,'' 
stresses that the allure of ``Star Wars'' was foremost in the 
storytelling, the mythological elements. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what will make or break this new one,'' he says.  
</P>
<P>
	And it is on this score that the early critics (many are holding  
their reviews until the release date) have been most unkind about 
``The Phantom Menace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``A brilliant technology achievement ... but a less emotionally  
resonant exercise,'' said Variety. ``He doesn't seem to care about 
building a character,'' said Newsweek. ``Needed more human and less 
digital scale,'' said the New York Daily News. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucas saw them coming. At the news conference, before the  
notices started rolling in, he said his ``Star Wars'' films have 
``mostly been trashed one way or another'' and ``I certainly expect 
not to do well critically.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But there was more to his preemptive reply. It spoke to the  
power of myth -- to transport, and to suffocate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the fans have unfortunately got themselves into a  
situation both from the fact they've gotten much older and that the 
film is really for young people,'' he said. ``They have these 
amazing expectations that the film can't possibly live up to.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
